# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: greek-alphabet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] Louis Braille's original publication, *Procedure for Writing Words, Music, and Plainsong in Dots* (1829), credits Barbier's night writing as being the basis for the braille script.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] It differed in a fundamental way from modern braille: It contained nine decades (series) of characters rather than the modern five, utilizing dashes as well as dots.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] Braille recognized, however, that the dashes were problematic, being difficult to distinguish from the dots in practice, and those characters were abandoned in the second edition of the book.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] The first four decades indicated the 40 letters of the alphabet (39 letters of the French alphabet, plus English *w*); the fifth the digits; the sixth punctuation; and the seventh and part of the eighth mathematical symbols.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] The seventh decade was also used for musical notes.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] Most of the remaining characters were unassigned.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] Thus the 1st and 5th decades occupied only the top half of the cell, while all characters in the other decades had a dot or dash in the bottom row.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] The supplemental signs were ⠄⠤⠜⠼ and a top dash with ⠠⠰.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] Of the 125 (53) possible patterns, 97 were used.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] The modern 5th decade and other supplemental signs do not appear in the 1829 version of braille, apart from ⠐ and ⠒ in plainsong notation.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] Anticipating that the dashes might prove problematic, Braille provided that the supplemental sign ⠼ (now known as the number sign) would shift the decade by four.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] That is, adding it to the first four decades would produce substitutes for the fifth through eighth.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] Only its use to replace the old fifth decade has been retained; the old sixth decade survives as the modern fifth, with the dash removed and the dots shifted down to replace it.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] The book allots a great deal of space to the representation of music.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] Instrumental notation was largely a one-to-one transcription of the system already in use for the blind.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] The durations of the notes and the accidentals, however, had to be replaced; for these the 7th decade was used, as shown in the table above.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] A simplified system for plainsong was provided.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] The twelve notes are the twelve characters of the upper half of the cell (the first and fifth decades) which do not have dashes.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] By themselves (1st decade), they indicate half notes.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] Quarter notes are 2nd decade, dotted quarter notes 3rd, and eighth notes 4th.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] Dotted half notes are indicated by a dash below (6th decade), whole notes by a dash above (7th decade), and dotted whole notes by a mid dash (8th decade).
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] The alto, bass, treble, and tenor clefs were indicated by the 5th–8th characters of the fifth decade. ⠐ is the sharp-note prefix, ⠒ the bass-note prefix, and the equivalent with a dash the natural prefix. ⠄⠤ are the repetition sign and 'star'.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] The book finishes with a proposal for braille shorthand, utilizing the first decade for vowels, and the fifth for consonants (without a voicing distinction).
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] That is, Braille's shorthand used a 4-dot cell rather than the standard 6-dot cell, taking two-thirds the space of normal braille, and one-third the space of Barbier's night writing.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] In the classroom, Braille's students found the characters with dashes to be impractical, as the dashes were not easily distinguishable from pairs of dots, and they were quickly abandoned.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] The second edition of the *Procédé*, published in 1837, sets out French Braille essentially as we know it today.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] According to Henri (1952), at right, the numerical sign was used with the new fifth decade, plus one of the supplementary characters, for mathematical notation: ⠼⠖ +, ⠼⠤ −, ⠼⠦ ×, ⠼⠲ /, ⠼⠶ =, ⠼⠜ √.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] Several of these values continue today in Antoine notation.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] The official Unicode encoding for Braille only specifies codepoints for modern dot-only patterns.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] An unofficial encoding for dash patterns can be found in the Under-ConScript Unicode Registry, and as such may be found in some fonts that cover characters from that agreement.
[src:greek-alphabet/1829-braille] Together, these two blocks can represent all cell definitions from the 1829 Braille specification.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The **2005 Atlantic hurricane season** was a record-breaking, catastrophic, and deadly Atlantic hurricane season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] It is the second-costliest hurricane season, just behind the 2017 season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] It featured 28 tropical and subtropical storms, which was previously the most recorded in a hurricane season until the 2020 season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The United States National Hurricane Center named 27 storms, exhausting the annual pre-designated list, requiring the use of six Greek letter names, and adding an additional unnamed subtropical storm during a post-season re-analysis.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] A record 15 storms attained hurricane status, with maximum sustained winds of at least 74 miles per hour (119 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Of those, a record seven became major hurricanes, rated Category 3 or higher on the Saffir–Simpson scale.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Four storms of this season became Category 5 hurricanes, the most of any season on record.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The four Category 5 hurricanes during the season were Emily, Katrina, Rita, and Wilma.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] In July, Emily reached peak intensity in the Caribbean Sea, becoming the first Category 5 hurricane of the season, later weakening and striking Mexico twice.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] It was the first Category 5 hurricane recorded in the month of July and was the earliest-forming Category 5 hurricane on record, until Hurricane Beryl surpassed the record in July 2024.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] In August, Katrina reached peak winds in the Gulf of Mexico but weakened by the time it struck the U.S. states of Louisiana and Mississippi.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The most devastating effects of the season were felt on the Gulf Coast of the United States, where Katrina's storm surge crippled New Orleans, Louisiana, for weeks and devastated the Mississippi coastline.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Katrina became the costliest U.S. hurricane, leaving $125 billion in damage and 1,392 deaths.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Rita followed in September, reaching peak intensity in the Gulf of Mexico before weakening and hitting near the border of Texas and Louisiana.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The season's strongest hurricane, Wilma, became the most intense Atlantic hurricane on record, as measured by barometric pressure.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Lasting for ten days in October, Wilma moved over Cozumel, the Yucatán Peninsula, and Florida, causing over $22 billion in damage and 52 deaths.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The season's impact was widespread and catastrophic.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Its storms caused an estimated 3,468 deaths and approximately $171.7 billion in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] It was the costliest season on record at the time, until its record was surpassed 12 years later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] It also produced the second-highest accumulated cyclone energy (ACE) in the Atlantic basin, only behind the 1933 season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The season officially began on June 1, 2005, and the first storm – Arlene – developed on June 8.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Hurricane Dennis in July inflicted heavy damage to Cuba.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Hurricane Stan in October was part of a broader weather system that killed 1,673 people and caused $3.96 billion in damage to eastern Mexico and Central America, with Guatemala hit the hardest.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The final storm – Zeta – formed in late December and lasted until January 6, 2006 – the latest of any season, tied with 1954–55.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Some forecasts predicted how many tropical cyclones would affect a particular country or territory.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The first of these forecasts was issued by CSU, which predicted on December 5, 2004 that the season would be above average and feature 11 named storms, 6 hurricanes and 3 intense hurricanes.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] They also noted that the Caribbean and the entire United States coastline faced an increased risk of a major hurricane making landfall.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] TSR issued its first forecast a few days later and predicted that the season would feature 9.6 tropical storms, 5.7 hurricanes, 3.3 major hurricanes, and predicted that the accumulated cyclone energy (ACE) rating would be 145.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] During January 2005, TSR increased its forecast to 13.9 tropical storms, 7.8 hurricanes, 3.6 major hurricanes, and predicted that the ACE rating would be 157.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] CSU issued its first updated forecast on April 1, increasing their prediction to 13 tropical storms, 7 hurricanes, and 3 major hurricanes, with a continued risk of a major hurricane landfall in the Caribbean or United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The increase was based on the Atlantic continuing to warm and a strong belief that El Niño conditions would not persist into the hurricane season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] On May 2, the Cuban Institute of Meteorology (InsMet) issued their seasonal forecast, which predicted that the season would feature 13 tropical storms and 7 hurricanes.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This was followed on May 16 by NOAA, who predicted a 70% chance of above normal activity, with 12–15 tropical storms, 7–9 hurricanes, and 3–5 major hurricanes.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The agency cited favorable conditions associated with an active phase of the Atlantic multidecadal oscillation (AMO).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] CSU issued its second forecast update on May 31, revising its forecast to 15 named storms, 8 hurricanes and 4 major hurricanes; by this point, the group believed El Niño conditions were unlikely.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] In their July forecast update, TSR anticipated that the season would be exceptionally active and well above average; the group increased their forecast to 15.3 tropical storms, 8.8 hurricanes, and 4.1 major hurricanes, with an ACE rating of 190.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] By the end of July, seven tropical storms and two major hurricanes had developed within the basin, which prompted CSU, InsMet, NOAA and TSR to significantly increase their seasonal forecasts at the start of August.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] In their August 5 update, CSU predicted that 13 more storms would form, with seven more hurricanes and three more major hurricanes.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] At the start of September, CSU updated their forecasts and predicted that eight more storms would form, with six more hurricanes and three major hurricanes.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] By the end of September, 17 named storms had developed, of which nine had developed into hurricanes and four had become major hurricanes.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Within their final update for the year, CSU predicted that October would feature three named storms, two hurricanes and one major hurricane.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] With 28 storms (27 named storms and one unnamed), the 2005 Atlantic hurricane season set a new single-year record for most storms, surpassing the total of 20 from 1933.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This record stood until surpassed by the 2020 season, which had 30 storms, making it the second-most active season on record .
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Before August 1, a record seven named storms formed, surpassing 1997, and later eclipsed by 2020.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Further, the months of July and November set records for number of named storms, with 5 and 3, respectively.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The 2005 season featured 15 hurricanes, surpassing the previous record of 12, set in 1969.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Of the 15 hurricanes, 5 formed in September, with the season becoming only the sixth to feature 5 in that month.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The 2005 season also featured a record seven major hurricanes, one more than the previous record, set in 1926, 1933, 1950, 1996, and 2004.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The four Category 5 hurricanes were also a record.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The season's activity was reflected with an ACE rating of 244, the second-highest value on record in the Atlantic basin, after the 1933 season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The storms of the season were extraordinarily damaging and were responsible for significant loss of life.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Total damage is estimated to be about US$171.7 billion, and the seasons' storms contributed to the deaths of 3,912 people.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] There were a record 15 storms making landfall, including seven storms that struck the United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The extremely active 2005 hurricane season was a continuation of an extended sequence of active years for tropical activity in the Atlantic.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Tropical cyclone activity in the Atlantic Ocean between 1995 and 2004 was more active than any other decade in reliable record.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] With the exception of two years in which El Niño conditions were prevalent (1997 and 2002), all hurricane seasons since 1995 were individually above average.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This was associated with an active phase of the Atlantic multidecadal oscillation (AMO), with a similar period of elevated tropical activity occurring between 1950 and 1969.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The anomalously frequent formation of tropical storms and hurricanes reflected the emergence of unusually warm sea surface temperatures across the tropical Atlantic.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Chylek and Lesins (2008) determined that the likelihood of a season generating as much tropical activity as 2005 was less than 1 percent.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The consecutive occurrence of hurricane seasons as active as 2004 and 2005 in the Atlantic was unprecedented.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] While environmental conditions favorable for the development of tropical cyclones were analogous to other active seasons, they were more pronounced and encompassed larger areas in 2005.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The multidecadal oscillation increased the potency of conducive environmental factors for tropical development, including the increased strength of subtropical ridges in the northern and southern Atlantic and the eastern Pacific.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This amplified the African easterly jet and enhanced upper-level easterlies, attenuating wind shear detrimental to tropical cyclogenesis across the central tropical Atlantic and the Caribbean.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Frequent lulls in convection over the tropical Pacific also contributed to the strength of these ridges, focusing hurricane activity in the Atlantic.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The Gulf of Mexico saw record levels of tropical activity in 2005, with 11 named storms entering the basin.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The unusual activity was attributed to a persistent high pressure area over the Southeastern United States, the northeastward displacement and amplification of the Intertropical Convergence Zone (ITCZ) over the eastern Pacific, and above average sea surface temperatures in the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] These factors reduced vertical wind shear and favored cyclonic flow, creating an environment highly supportive of tropical development.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The high pressure area also steered incoming storms into the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] In addition, the El Niño–Southern Oscillation (ENSO) was in a neutral phase, lowering the likelihood of storms making landfall on the East Coast of the United States and leading to a concentration of impacts farther west.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This focusing mechanism led to a complementary reduction in storms developing close to Cape Verde.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] During the peak of the 2005 season, the Loop Current – an ocean current that transports warm water from the Caribbean Sea northward into the Gulf of Mexico and offshore the U.S.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] East Coast – propagated northward, reaching its most poleward point in advance of Hurricane Katrina.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This protrusion detached into a warm core ring, or a small region of warm waters to an abnormally deep depth, and began to drift southwest as Hurricane Rita traversed the region.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] By mid-October, the Loop Current returned to its typical position in the Yucatán Peninsula.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This evolution provided enhanced ocean heat content to both hurricanes and was partially responsible for the extreme intensities attained by those cyclones.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Lowered sea-level atmospheric pressures in the late spring and early summer of 2005 curtailed the strength of trade winds.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This allowed the persistence of the anomalously warm sea surface temperatures until November 2005.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The activity in later parts of the 2005 season was elevated by the unusual development of four tropical cyclones from non-tropical origins over the eastern Atlantic.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] In the wake of the season, questions arose regarding the potential impact of global warming on Atlantic hurricane activity.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Hurricane experts noted that establishing a conclusive relationship would be difficult given the significant role that natural variability plays on hurricane formation and significantly improved tropical cyclone detection methods compared to decades past.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] A series of international workshops were established after 2005.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] After five years of analysis, researchers were unable to confirm whether the recent increase in tropical cyclone activity could be attributed more to climate change than natural variability.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Models developed within the workshops projected that the number of tropical cyclones under Category 3 intensity would fall over the 21st century, while the number of intense Category 4–5 hurricanes would increase significantly.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] One potential hypothesis for these findings was a projected increase in vertical wind shear contradicted by warmer ocean temperatures for hurricanes to utilize.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The team also concluded that the amount of precipitation produced by tropical cyclones would increase over the next century.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] In May 2020, researchers at the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and the University of Wisconsin at Madison built upon this research and, for the first time, established a statistically significant global trend toward more intense tropical cyclones, particularly in the Atlantic basin.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The research not only reaffirmed a trend toward stronger, wetter tropical cyclones, but it also identified a trend toward increased rapid intensification events and a general slowing of tropical cyclones' forward motion near land.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The season's first tropical depression developed north of Honduras on June 8.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving generally northward, it intensified into Tropical Storm Arlene, and struck western Cuba on June 10.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm reached peak winds of 70 mph (110 km/h) early on June 11.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Later that day, the storm moved ashore just west of Pensacola, Florida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Over the next two days, Arlene continued northward through the United States, dissipating over southeastern Canada on June 14.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In western Cuba, Arlene produced wind gusts of 49 mph (79 km/h) at Punta del Este and 6.81 in (173 mm) of rainfall in the city of Pinar del Río.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Arlene left mostly minor damage throughout the United States, estimated at $11.8 million.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Miami Beach, Florida, a student died when she was caught in a rip current.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Rainfall in the United States peaked at 9.84 in (250 mm) in Lake Toxaway, North Carolina.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical depression formed on June 28 in the Bay of Campeche.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It quickly strengthened into Tropical Storm Bret with sustained winds of 40 mph (64 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Bret moved ashore northeastern Mexico near Tuxpan, Veracruz, dissipating early on June 30 over San Luis Potosí.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Bret brought heavy rainfall across Mexico, reaching at least 10.47 in (266 mm) in El Raudal, Veracruz.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] One person drowned in Cerro Azul, while another death occurred in Naranjos due to cardiac arrest.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The floods forced the evacuation of approximately 2,800 people, damaged around 3,000 houses, isolated 66 villages, and caused about $100 million (MXN, US$9.2 million) in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical depression formed on July 3 in the western Caribbean Sea, and crossed the Yucatán Peninsula into the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It strengthened into Tropical Storm Cindy early on July 5, and attained hurricane status a day later, with peak winds of 75 mph (120 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Early on July 6, Cindy struck southeastern Louisiana, and after weakening over land, hit southern Mississippi as a tropical storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Cindy continued across the southeastern United States and transitioned into an extratropical cyclone on July 7 over The Carolinas; it eventually dissipated over the Gulf of St.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Across the United States, the hurricane caused $320 million in damage and three fatalities – one in Georgia from flooding, and two in Maryland from a car crash.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Across Louisiana, the hurricane left 280,000 people without power.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Rainfall in the United States peaked at 9.50 in (241 mm) in Saint Bernard, Louisiana.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Cindy spawned a large tornado outbreak, including an F2 tornado near Hampton, Georgia, that caused over $40 million in damage at the Atlanta Motor Speedway alone.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The same tornado damaged planes and helicopters at Tara Field, as well as hundreds of homes.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Tropical Depression Four formed in the southeastern Caribbean late on July 4, and further strengthened into Tropical Storm Dennis early the next day.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm moved west-northwestward, strengthening into a hurricane on July 6 to the south of Hispaniola.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On the next day, Dennis rapidly intensified into a Category 4 hurricane while moving between Jamaica and Haiti.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Early on July 8, the hurricane briefly moved over Granma Province in southeastern Cuba.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] After briefly weakening, Dennis restrengthened to attain peak winds of 150 mph (240 km/h) in the Gulf of Guacanayabo.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Later on July 8, Dennis moved ashore again in Matanzas Province.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane crossed Cuba entered the Gulf of Mexico on July 9 as a weakened hurricane.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Dennis re-intensified to a secondary peak of 145 mph (233 km/h) on July 10, only to weaken prior to its final landfall later that day near Pensacola, Florida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Dennis weakened and moved through the southeastern United States, the Ohio Valley, and eventually dissipating on July 18 over Ontario.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The outer rainbands of Dennis produced widespread flooding and landslides in Haiti, killing at least 56 people and leaving US$50 million in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Dennis brought torrential rain to Jamaica, reaching 24.54 in (623 mm) in Mavis Bank.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] One person died in Jamaica, and damage was estimated at US$31.7 million.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm's heaviest rainfall occurred in Cuba, reaching 43.0 in (1,092 mm).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Across the island, Dennis killed 16 people, and left US$1.4 billion in damage, affecting agriculture, tourist areas, infrastructure, and houses.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Dennis moved ashore Florida near where Hurricane Ivan struck ten months prior.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage from Dennis in the United States totaled $2.545 billion, and there were 15 deaths in the country, all but one in Florida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Rainfall in the United States reached 12.80 in (325 mm) near Camden, Alabama.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On July 11, a tropical depression formed east of the Lesser Antilles, which quickly intensified into Tropical Storm Emily.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving westward, Emily strengthened into a minimal hurricane and struck Grenada at that intensity on July 14.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Continuing across the Caribbean Sea, Emily eventually strengthened into a Category 5 hurricane on July 16 to the southwest of Jamaica, reaching peak winds of 160 mph (260 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Emily weakened after its peak intensity, striking the northeastern Yucatán Peninsula on July 18 with winds of 135 mph (217 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Emily emerged into the Gulf of Mexico and restrengthened, making another landfall in Mexico on July 18 in Tamaulipas with winds of 125 mph (201 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A day later, Emily dissipated over land.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] While moving through the Lesser Antilles, the hurricane produced strong winds and heavy rainfall that caused flooding and landslides across several islands.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Grenada, a man died when a landslide destroyed his house.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane damaged or destroyed 2,641 homes in the country, leaving 167 families homeless.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Emily left US$111 million in damage when it struck Grenada.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Flooding rains killed ten people in Haiti.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Jamaica, Emily produced 15.43 in (392 mm) of rainfall; associated flooding killed five people on the island.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Collectively, Emily and earlier Hurricane Dennis left about US$96 million (J$6 billion) in damage to Jamaica.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Honduras, a man drowned in a river swollen by rains from Emily.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Across Mexico, Emily's damage was estimated at Mex$3.427 billion (US$322 million), resulting in disaster areas across four states.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] There were five deaths in the country related to Emily.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The outskirts of Emily dropped heavy rainfall in southern Texas, damaging about $4.7 million worth of cotton.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Tropical Depression Six formed northeast of the Bahamas on July 21, originating from a tropical wave that exited the coast of Africa on July 10.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The depression quickly intensified into Tropical Storm Franklin, but wind shear disrupted the storm's initial development.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] As the storm moved to the north and northeast, it intensified; on July 23, Franklin attained peak winds of 70 mph (110 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Three days later the storm passed west of Bermuda.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] An approaching trough turned Franklin to the northwest and weakened Franklin to a minimal tropical storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Franklin restrengthened slightly as it accelerated northeastward.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On July 30, the storm transitioned into an extratropical cyclone south of Nova Scotia, and a day later it was absorbed by a larger extratropical storm near Newfoundland.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On July 26, Bermuda recorded wind gusts of 37 mph (60 km/h) while the storm made its closest approach.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm brought light rainfall to Newfoundland.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The same tropical wave that spawned Tropical Storm Franklin later led to the formation of a tropical depression in the Bay of Campeche on July 23.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It intensified into Tropical Storm Gert early on July 24, and quickly moved ashore north of Cabo Rojo, Mexico, with 45 mph (72 km/h) winds early on July 25.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It continued inland, affecting the same areas impacted by Hurricane Emily just days prior, and quickly dissipated over high terrain at the end of that day.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Gert dropped heavy rainfall, reaching 8.46 in (214.9 mm) in San Luis Potosí.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Gert caused about US$6 million ($60 million 2005 MXN) in damage, and resulted in one fatality in Nuevo León.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Tropical Depression Eight formed on August 2 southwest of Bermuda from a tropical wave that left the African coast on July 22.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The depression strengthened into Tropical Storm Harvey on August 3 while moving northeastward.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Due to strong wind shear, Harvey initially exhibited subtropical characteristics.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On August 4, Harvey passed 45 miles (72 km) south of Bermuda.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] After moving away from the island, Harvey attained peak winds of 65 mph (105 km/h) late on August 4 and continued northeastward for a few days, transitioning into an extratropical storm on August 9.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm gradually weakened and eventually dissipated northwest of the Azores on August 14.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Bermuda, Harvey dropped 5.02 in (128 mm) of rainfall at Bermuda International Airport, flooding some roads.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Sustained winds on the island reached 45 mph (72 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical wave exited west Africa on August 1, and three days later developed into a tropical depression to the southwest of the Cabo Verde islands.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Despite wind shear, the depression strengthened into Tropical Storm Irene on August 7 as it moved northwestward.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Dry air weakened Irene back to tropical depression status, but after reaching warmer waters, it restrengthened into a tropical storm on August 11.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A weakness in the subtropical ridge allowed Irene to turn sharply northward, which caused the storm to pass midway between the Outer Banks of North Carolina and Bermuda on August 15.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] After a decrease in wind shear, Irene strengthened into a hurricane on August 16, reaching peak winds of 105 mph (170 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 970 mbar (29 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It again encountered wind shear, causing it to weaken back to tropical storm status on August 18.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] That day, Irene was absorbed by a larger extratropical storm southeast of Newfoundland.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane generated strong waves and rip currents along the East Coast of the United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Near Long Beach, New York, rip currents near Long Beach killed a 16-year-old boy.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Many beaches in New Jersey restricted swimming activities, and lifeguards at one beach performed more than a hundred rescues over a three-day period.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Tropical Depression Ten formed between the Lesser Antilles and Cape Verde on August 13 from a tropical wave that entered the Atlantic five days earlier.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The depression moved slowly westward in an environment of strong vertical shear.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Some weather models predicted relaxing shear and intensification of the system; however, the hostile conditions ripped the system apart, causing the depression to degenerate into a remnant low, and the NHC discontinued advisories on August 14, when no organized deep convection remained.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The remnants of Tropical Depression Ten continued drifting northwestward, before degenerating further into a tropical wave north of the Leeward Islands, on August 18.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Soon afterward, the low-level and mid-level circulations split, with the mid-level circulation lagging behind to the east.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The remnant low-level circulation continued westward, before dissipating near Cuba on August 21.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Producing occasional bursts of convection, the mid-level remnant circulation eventually merged with another tropical wave, which later produced Hurricane Katrina, approaching from the east, on August 19.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical depression developed in the Bay of Campeche on August 22, which quickly strengthened into Tropical Storm Jose.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm reached a maximum strength of 60 mph (97 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Jose made landfall in the Mexican state of Veracruz near the Laguna Verde Nuclear Power Station on August 23, and rapidly dissipated over land.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] While drenching Mexico's Gulf coast, Jose forced some 25,000 residents from their homes in Veracruz state and damaged at least 16,000 homes in the state.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Jose killed 11 people in Veracruz and 5 in Oaxaca.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage in Mexico totaled roughly $45 million.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical depression developed on August 23 from the complex interaction of a tropical wave, the mid-level remnants of Tropical Depression Ten, and a nearby upper-level trough.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The depression became a tropical storm on August 24 and a hurricane on August 25, making landfall as a Category 1 hurricane in southeastern Florida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Katrina imparted about $500 million in crop and infrastructure damage to the state.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane quickly crossed Florida and emerged into the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Katrina rapidly intensified to Category 5 status early on August 28, becoming the seventh most intense Atlantic hurricane.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Turning northward, the hurricane weakened as it approached the northern Gulf Coast.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On August 29 at 11:10 UTC, Katrina made landfall in southeastern Louisiana as a Category 3 hurricane, with 125 mph (201 km/h) winds, and a barometric pressure of 920 mbar (27 inHg); it was the third lowest pressure for a landfalling United States hurricane at the time, and fourth as of 2018.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Katrina then crossed the Breton Sound, making a third and final landfall with 120 mph (190 km/h) winds near Pearlington, Mississippi.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The cyclone quickly weakened after moving inland and became extratropical over Kentucky on August 30.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On August 28, the New Orleans National Weather Service issued an urgent weather bulletin describing potentially catastrophic impacts, comparing Katrina to Hurricane Camille of 1969.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] That same day, New Orleans mayor Ray Nagin issued the city's first-ever mandatory evacuation.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] About 80% of the city and 83% of neighboring Jefferson Parish evacuated ahead of the storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane left catastrophic damage across southern Louisiana, with more than 300,000 houses damaged or destroyed; most of these were in Orleans Parish.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In New Orleans, a storm surge breached the levees along the Gulf Intracoastal Waterway and 17th Street and London Avenue Canals, flooding about 80% of the city.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Portions of the city remained underwater for 43 days.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The Mississippi and Alabama coastlines also suffered catastrophic damage from the storm's 30 ft (9.1 m) storm surge, with very few structures remaining on the coast of the former.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Across the region, the hurricane flooded and ruined about 350,000 vehicles.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] About 2.4 million people lost access to clean drinking water.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Katrina also spawned an outbreak of 62 tornadoes across the eight states in the eastern United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Hurricane Katrina imparted catastrophic damage in portions of Louisiana and Mississippi.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Total damage has been estimated at $125 billion, making Katrina the costliest hurricane in U.S. history, surpassing Andrew in 1992 and later tied by Harvey in 2017.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Throughout the United States, Katrina killed 1,392 people, making it one of the deadliest hurricanes in the United States, and the deadliest American hurricane since 1928.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) managed the aftermath of the hurricane, and faced criticism for its response time, lack of coordination with state agencies, supply shortages, and insufficient housing for federal workers.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Tens of thousands of people lost their jobs following the hurricane.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Residents across the New Orleans area suffered health effects, including rashes and respiratory problems, from polluted water and air following the hurricane.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Katrina forced about 800,000 people to move temporarily, which was the greatest number of displaced people in the country since the Dust Bowl.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The United States federal government spent $110.6 billion in relief, recovery and rebuilding efforts, including $16 billion toward rebuilding houses, which was the nation's largest ever housing recovery project.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Within a year of the storm, most of the levees were largely repaired.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Various countries and international agencies sent supplies or financial aid to assist in the hurricane response.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical wave moved off the coast of Africa on August 24.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It developed into Tropical Depression Thirteen on August 28 while 960 miles (1,540 km) east of the Lesser Antilles.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Strong wind shear prevented much organization, and the depression degenerated into a low pressure area late on August 29.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The remnants moved to the north and northeast, steered by a larger non-tropical system to the north.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The convection increased on August 31; that day the system regenerated into a tropical depression, which strengthened further into Tropical Storm Lee.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm attained peak winds of 40 mph (64 km/h) while located between Bermuda and the Azores.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] After 12 hours as a tropical storm, Lee weakened back to a tropical depression as it turned to the northwest, steered by the larger non-tropical storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 2, the depression degenerated into a remnant low, which was absorbed by a cold front two days later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A powerful tropical wave moved off the coast of Africa on August 27.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] As it moved west into the Atlantic, it became more organized and the system developed into Tropical Depression Fourteen about midway between Cape Verde and the Lesser Antilles on September 1.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Shear from an upper-level low to the southwest slowed the development.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The depression gradually strengthened as it moved to the northwest across the open Atlantic Ocean, becoming Tropical Storm Maria on September 2 and reaching hurricane strength on September 4.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In the central Atlantic, Hurricane Maria continued to strengthen in favorable conditions, and on September 5 briefly became a Category 3 hurricane with 115 mph (185 km/h) winds while 480 miles (770 km) east of Bermuda.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Increasing shear and cooler waters caused the storm to rapidly weaken to a minimal hurricane on September 7.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The interaction with a trough caused Maria to restrengthen slightly, as it curved to the northeast, moving around the subtropical ridge.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Maria then weakened to a tropical storm, transitioning into an extratropical cyclone on September 10.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The former hurricane restrengthened over the northern Atlantic Ocean, only to weaken again as the storm passed south of Iceland.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 14, the extratropical storm that was once Maria merged with another extratropical storm while approaching Norway.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The remnants of Maria brought resulted in heavy rainfall to Norway, triggering a landslide in Bergen that killed three people and injured seven others.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical depression formed on September 5 south-southwest of Bermuda on September 5.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It quickly intensified into Tropical Storm Nate, which moved slowly northeastward.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 7, Nate intensified into the seventh hurricane of the season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A day later, the hurricane passed southeast of Bermuda, where it produced wind gusts of 50 mph (80 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Early on September 9, Nate attained peak winds of 90 mph (140 km/h), before weakening due to an approaching trough.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 10, Nate transitioned into an extratropical storm, which was absorbed by a larger extratropical storm near the Azores on September 13.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Gulf Coast to help in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina were slowed down trying to avoid Nate and Ophelia.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Rip currents caused by hurricanes Nate and Maria killed one person in New Jersey and severely injured another person.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Tropical Depression Sixteen formed over the northern Bahamas on September 6.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The depression strengthened into Tropical Storm Ophelia on September 7 and briefly into a hurricane on September 9.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Ophelia fluctuated between hurricane and tropical storm intensity for the next week as it meandered off the southeastern United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Twice it attained peak winds of 85 mph (137 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 14, the northern eyewall moved over the North Carolina coast from Wilmington to Morehead City.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] After moving away from the state, Ophelia weakened to tropical storm status due to stronger wind shear and dry air.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm accelerated northeastward and passed southeast of Cape Cod.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Ophelia transitioned into an extratropical storm on September 18 and subsequently crossed Nova Scotia and Newfoundland, eventually dissipating on September 23 north of the Scandinavian Peninsula.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Ophelia caused significant coastal erosion from the churning waves.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane caused extensive damage in the Outer Banks and around Cape Fear.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage in the United States was estimated at $70 million.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm's remnants produced strong winds and heavy rain over Atlantic Canada.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Ophelia killed three people – a drowning in Florida from high surf, a traffic fatality in North Carolina, and a death from a fall in Nova Scotia.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 17, Tropical Depression Seventeen formed from a tropical wave about 350 miles (560 km) east of Barbados.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It quickly intensified into Tropical Storm Philippe while taking a track to the north-northwest.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Early on September 19, Philippe attained hurricane status and reached peak winds of 80 mph (130 km/h) a day later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Wind shear from an upper-level low caused the hurricane to weaken back to a tropical storm, exposing the center from the convection.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 21, Philippe accelerated to the north and began moving around the upper-level low, which had extended to the surface and developed into a non-tropical cyclone.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm briefly threatened Bermuda as it turned to the northwest and began a counterclockwise loop.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 23, Philippe weakened to a tropical depression and later a remnant low; it was absorbed by the larger non-tropical cyclone a day later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Philippe brought gusty winds and moisture to Bermuda, with 0.15 inches (3.8 mm) of precipitation reported on September 23.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The circulation that absorbed Philippe dropped light rainfall on the island, and was responsible for the lowest barometric pressure during the month.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical depression formed on September 18 near the Turks and Caicos Islands on September 18, and soon strengthened into Tropical Storm Rita.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving to the west-northwest, Rita continued to intensify, becoming a hurricane on September 20 between Cuba and Florida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Rapid intensification ensued as Rita moved into the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Late on September 21, Rita strengthened into a Category 5 hurricane, and the next day it attained peak winds of 180 mph (290 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Its minimum pressure of 895 mbar (895 hPa; 26.4 inHg) was the lowest of any storm in the Gulf of Mexico on record, later being tied with Hurricane Milton in 2024.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane weakened as it approached the northwest Gulf Coast.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 24, Rita made landfall near the Texas–Louisiana border with sustained winds of 115 mph (185 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It rapidly weakened over land as it turned to the north and northeast, and was later absorbed by an approaching cold front on September 26 over Illinois.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Across the United States, Rita imparted $18.5 billion in damage and killed 120 people, although only seven deaths were directly related to the hurricane.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Early in its evolution, Rita flooded houses in northern Cuba and the Florida Keys.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Gulf Coast prompted one of the largest mass evacuations in the country's history, with an estimated 3.7 million people fleeing the Texas coast between Corpus Christi and Beaumont.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Due in part to high temperatures preceding Rita's landfall and elderly susceptibility to excessive heat, at least 80 people died during the mass evacuation; a coach fire en route to Dallas claimed 23 lives.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Rita generated a 15-foot (4.6 m) storm surge that devastated parts of Cameron Parish in Louisiana, destroying most structures in towns like Cameron and Holly Beach.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Storm surge also damaged homes in adjoining Jefferson County in Texas.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In New Orleans, Rita produced additional flooding and overtopped levees that had been repaired after Hurricane Katrina a month earlier.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Impacts from heavy rainfall, gusty winds, and tornadoes associated with Rita affected much of the lower Mississippi River Valley, and over a million electricity customers lost power.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A third of Cameron Parish's population left the parish following the devastation wrought by Rita.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 30, a tropical wave developed into Tropical Depression Nineteen to the west of Cabo Verde.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The newly formed cyclone exhibited deep convection in the southern semicircle, but its cloud pattern quickly deteriorated under the influence of strong wind shear.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The system moved northwestward and failed to intensify beyond winds of 35 mph (56 km/h), instead dissipating on October 2 without affecting land.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical depression formed southeast of Cozumel on October 1, and quickly strengthened into Tropical Storm Stan before hitting the Yucatan Peninsula.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Stan weakened to a tropical depression over land, but soon re-intensified over water.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Stan became a hurricane, attaining peak winds of 80 mph (130 km/h), before making a second landfall in the Mexican state of Veracruz early on October 4.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Stan rapidly weakened over land, dissipating early on October 5.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Stan killed 80 people in Mexico, and damage in the county was estimated at US$1.2 billion ($13.2 billion MXN).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Stan was associated with a larger weather system across eastern Mexico and Central America.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Torrential rainfall across this region killed 1,513 people in Guatemala, making it the deadliest natural disaster in the country's history.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage in Guatemala was estimated at US$996 million.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] El Salvador's Santa Ana Volcano erupted on October 1, occurring simultaneous to the flooding.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The flooding killed 69 people in the country, and damage from the two disasters was estimated at US$355.6 million.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Honduras, the weather system killed seven people and left US$100 million in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] There were also three deaths in Nicaragua and one in Costa Rica.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Road damage in Costa Rica from Stan and earlier Hurricane Rita was estimated at US$57 million (₡28 billion (CRC).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 28, an upper-level low formed west of the Canary Islands and moved to the west-northwest.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Two days later, the low spawned a surface trough along with scattered convection.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Late on October 3, a surface low formed about 460 mi (740 km) southwest of São Miguel Island in the Azores.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It organized into a subtropical depression early on October 4, based on the system's broad wind field.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It turned to the northeast ahead of an approaching cold front, and soon strengthened into a subtropical storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm reached peak winds of 50 mph (85 km/h) as it moved through the eastern Azores.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Santa Maria Island reported wind gusts of 59 mph (94 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Early on October 5, the storm merged with the cold front, and later that day, its remains were absorbed by a non-tropical low.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The low that absorbed the storm would eventually become Hurricane Vince.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] This system was not noted during the season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It was identified by the National Hurricane Center as a subtropical storm during post-season analysis.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On October 5, Tropical Storm Tammy developed east of Florida following the interaction of a tropical wave and an upper-level trough.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] That day, it strengthened to reach peak winds of 50 mph (80 km/h) and made landfall near Jacksonville, Florida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Tammy weakened as it moved inland, crossing southern Georgia and Alabama.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It was absorbed by a larger extratropical storm on October 6.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Tammy dropped locally heavy rainfall along its path, causing minor damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The frontal system that absorbed Tammy was a partial cause for severe flooding in New York, New Jersey and New England that killed 10 people in mid-October.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A surface trough developed on October 6, partially aided by outflow from Tropical Storm Tammy.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It organized enough to be classified Subtropical Depression Twenty-Two on October 8, about 450 miles (720 km) southeast of Bermuda on October 8.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The NHC classified it subtropical due to the nearby presence of an upper-level low.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The depression encountered strong wind shear, and it degenerated into a remnant low on October 10 about 175 mi (280 km) southwest of Bermuda.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The low merged with a cold front on October 11, and over the next three days it meandered off the east coast of the United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On October 14, a larger extratropical storm absorbed the former subtropical depression.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The system produced heavy rainfall across the northeastern United States from October 14 to 16, reaching over 6 in (150 mm), just days after the region received rainfall from the remnants of Tropical Storm Tammy.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Two people died in Connecticut after they were swept away by floods.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] About 500 people in Rhode Island required rescue, after the rains led to river flooding.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Subtropical Storm Vince formed in the eastern Atlantic near Madeira on October 8 from the same non-tropical low that absorbed the unnamed subtropical storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Vince transitioned into a tropical storm on the following day and was upgraded to a hurricane shortly thereafter.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Although Vince was a very small and short-lived storm that only briefly reached hurricane strength, it was notable for developing in the northeastern Atlantic, well away from where hurricanes usually form.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Vince made landfall on the Iberian Peninsula near Huelva, Spain, on October 11 just after weakening to a tropical depression.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm left minor flooding in some areas.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical depression formed on October 15 to the southwest of Jamaica.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving slowly over the Caribbean, it intensified into Tropical Storm Wilma two days later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm began a period of rapid deepening on October 18 that lasted into the following day.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] This culminated in Wilma attaining Category 5 hurricane status, with peak winds of 185 mph (298 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] At 12:00 UTC on October 19, hurricane hunters recorded a pressure of 882 mbar (26.0 inHg), making Wilma the most-intense Atlantic hurricane on record.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Wilma weakened to Category 4 intensity by the time it made landfall on Cozumel on October 21.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It crossed the Yucatán Peninsula and emerged into the Gulf of Mexico, turning northeast.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On October 24, Wilma made landfall in southwestern Florida at Cape Romano with winds of 120 mph (190 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane quickly crossed the state and continued across the western Atlantic Ocean.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Wilma transitioned into an extratropical cyclone on October 26, which was absorbed by a larger extratropical storm a day later over Atlantic Canada.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In its formative stages, Wilma's large circulation spread across much of the western Caribbean Sea, killing 12 people in Haiti and one in Jamaica.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Wilma set a record in Mexico, and for the entire Western Hemisphere, for the highest 24 hour rainfall total, with 64.330 in (1,633.98 mm) recorded at Isla Mujeres.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] There were four deaths in Mexico, and nationwide damage was estimated at US$454 million ($4.8 billion MXN).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On November 28, Mexico declared a disaster area for 9 of Quintana Roo's 11 municipalities.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A significant storm surge flooded areas of western Cuba, leaving US$704 million in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Florida, Wilma caused $19 billion in damage and killed 30 people; five of the deaths were caused directly by the hurricane.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Wilma inflicted a multi-billion dollar disaster in the Miami metropolitan area, including $2.9 billion in damage in Palm Beach County, $2 billion in Miami-Dade County, and $1.2 billion in Broward County.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Numerous homes and businesses experienced some degree of impact, with over 55,000 dwellings and 3,600 workplaces damaged in Palm Beach County alone.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] After leaving Florida, Wilma killed one person and left US$6.4 million in damage to the Bahamas, when it passed northwest of the country.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On Bermuda, Wilma produced wind gusts of 51 mph (82 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Tropical Depression Twenty-Five formed in the eastern Caribbean on October 22 and quickly intensified into Tropical Storm Alpha as it moved west-northwestward.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On the next day, the storm made landfall near Barahona, Dominican Republic, with winds of 50 mph (80 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Alpha weakened to a tropical depression over Hispaniola's steep mountains.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The cyclone emerged into the Atlantic Ocean, where it was absorbed by Hurricane Wilma on October 24.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm claimed 26 lives, with more than half of them in Haiti.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Alpha destroyed 43 homes and damaged 191 others in Haiti.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Late on October 26, the same tropical wave that spawned Tropical Storm Alpha led to the formation of Tropical Depression Twenty-Six over the southwestern Caribbean Sea.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Early the next day, it was upgraded to Tropical Storm Beta.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm strengthened into a hurricane on October 29 and reached major hurricane intensity on October 30, with sustained winds around 115 mph (185 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] However, Beta weakened to a Category 2 prior to landfall in Nicaragua.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm rapidly weakened inland and dissipated on October 31.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The Colombian island of Providencia was subjected to hurricane-force winds for several hours as the center of the storm moved very slowly by the island.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Reports indicate extensive damage to homes and a loss of communications with the islanders.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Honduras and Nicaragua, over 1,000 structures were damaged by the storm, hundreds of which were destroyed.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Overall, Beta caused nine fatalities and more than $15.5 million in damage across four countries.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical depression formed late on November 13 about 115 mi (185 km) west-southwest of St.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] While passing through the Lesser Antilles, the system produced heavy rainfall and mudslides, killing two people on Bequia in St.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The depression briefly attained tropical storm status, but degenerated back into a tropical wave.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On November 18, a new circulation formed off the north coast of Honduras, developing into Tropical Storm Gamma, with peak winds of 50 mph (85 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Gamma meandered over the western Caribbean until degenerating into a remnant low on November 21.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Floods from Gamma killed 34 people in Honduras.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Three people died in Belize related to the storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A non-tropical low formed in the open Atlantic on November 19, which developed thunderstorms over the center over the next few days.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On November 22, the NHC classified it as Subtropical Storm Delta, and redesignated it as a tropical storm the next day.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Delta moved to the south and stalled, becoming a strong tropical storm with peak winds of 70 mph (110 km/h) on November 24.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It weakened as it accelerated to the east-northeast, and Delta transitioned into an extratropical storm on November 28.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Shortly thereafter, the storm passed just north of the Canary Islands before Delta inland over northwest Africa, dissipating on November 29.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Delta caused severe damage in the Canary Islands and claimed at least seven lives, including six who drowned after boats overturned; there were 12 people missing from the overturned boat.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] 'Finger of God'), a geological feature which had been pointing towards the sky for over a millennium and an important landmark for the Canary Islands, was toppled during the storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage throughout the Canary Islands was estimated at €312 million (US$364 million).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Delta also caused power outages, leaving some 200,000 people without power and forcing airports to close down.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The remnants of Delta later moved into Morocco, bringing needed rain.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A surface low attached to a stationary front formed underneath an upper-level low east of Bermuda on November 27.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The surface low detached from the frontal zone and acquired tropical characteristics as deep convection wrapped around its center, leading to the development of Tropical Storm Epsilon early on November 29.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The NHC consistently forecast that the storm would weaken; however, Epsilon gradually intensified as it moved westward and later looped to the northeast.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm attained hurricane status on December 2 as the track shifted to the east.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Neither Epsilon's structure or strength changed appreciably over the next few days, and it attained peak winds of 85 mph (137 km/h) on December 5.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A building ridge turned Epsilon to the southwest on December 6, and it maintained its intensity due to low wind shear.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Epsilon remained a hurricane until December 7.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Epsilon degenerated into a remnant low on December 8; the circulation dissipated two days later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Towards the end of December, an upper-level low interacted with a cold front, which produced an area of low-pressure by December 28, about 750 mi (1,205 km) to the west-northwest of Cabo Verde.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Over the next couple of days, the system developed a low-level circulation and atmospheric convection increased as it moved north-westwards, before the NHC classified it as Tropical Storm Zeta during December 30.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Over the next couple of days, the system gradually intensified further in a region of favorable anticyclonic outflow, as it slowly moved west-northwest in response to a mid-level low to the southwest.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On January 1, Zeta peaked with 1-minute sustained winds of 65 mph (105 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It weakened on January 2, only to re-intensify to its peak intensity on January 3.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Zeta weakened again as it turned westward, degenerating into a remnant low on January 6; the circulation dissipated on the next day to the southeast of Bermuda.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Zeta affected the 2005 Atlantic Rowing Race by producing high swells that moved boats off course.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The following list of names was used for named storms that formed in the North Atlantic in 2005.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] This was the same list used for the 1999 season, with the exceptions of *Franklin* and *Lee*, which replaced *Floyd* and *Lenny*.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] This was the first Atlantic hurricane season to exhaust the designated list of 21 storm names, and the first to utilize the auxiliary list.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In the spring of 2006, the hurricane committee of the World Meteorological Organization (WMO) retired five names: *Dennis*, *Katrina*, *Rita*, *Stan*, and *Wilma*, from the Atlantic hurricane name lists, and they will not be used again.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] They were replaced with *Don*, *Katia*, *Rina*, *Sean* and *Whitney* for the 2011 season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] This set a new record for the number of storm names retired from a single season, surpassing the previous record of four names, held by the 1955, 1995, 2004 seasons.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] There was considerable discussion at that time on the usage of the Greek alphabet.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It was also decided that it was not practical to retire a Greek letter.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Storms named with Greek letters that would otherwise be eligible for retirement would appear in the retired name list, but have a notation affixed with the circumstances.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] However, when faced with retiring Eta and Iota following the 2020 season, when the Greek alphabet was next utilized, the WMO decided to discontinue its further use altogether.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A new auxiliary list of given names was implemented, making any retirements less problematic.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] This is a table of all of the storms that formed in the 2005 Atlantic hurricane season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It includes their name, duration, peak classification and intensities, areas affected, damage, and death totals.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Deaths in parentheses are additional and indirect (an example of an indirect death would be a traffic accident), but were still related to that storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2005-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage and deaths include totals while the storm was extratropical, a wave, or a low, and all of the damage figures are in 2005 USD.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The **2020 Atlantic hurricane season** was the most active Atlantic hurricane season on record, in terms of the number of systems.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] It featured a total of 31 tropical and subtropical cyclones, with all but one becoming a named storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Of the 30 named storms, 14 developed into hurricanes, and a record-tying seven further intensified into major hurricanes.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] It was the second and final season to use the Greek letter storm naming system, the first being 2005, the previous record.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Of the 30 named storms, 11 of them made landfall in the contiguous United States, breaking the record of nine set in 1916.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] During the season, 27 tropical storms established a new record for earliest formation date by storm number.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This season also featured a record ten tropical cyclones that underwent rapid intensification, tying it with 1995, as well as tying the record for most Category 4 hurricanes in a singular season in the Atlantic basin.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This unprecedented activity was fueled by a La Niña that developed in the summer months of 2020, continuing a stretch of above-average seasonal activity that began in 2016.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Despite the record-high activity, this was the first season since 2015 in which no Category 5 hurricanes formed.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The season officially started on June 1 and officially ended on November 30.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] However, tropical cyclogenesis is possible at any time of the year, as demonstrated by the early formation of Tropical Storms Arthur and Bertha, on May 16 and 27, respectively.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This was the sixth consecutive year with a pre-season system and the second of these seasons to have two, with the other being 2016.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The first hurricane, Hurricane Hanna, made landfall in Texas on July 25.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Hurricane Isaias formed on July 31, and made landfall in The Bahamas and North Carolina in early August, both times as a Category 1 hurricane; Isaias caused $4.8 billion in damage overall.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] In late August, Laura made landfall in Louisiana as a Category 4 hurricane, becoming the strongest tropical cyclone on record in terms of wind speed to make landfall in the state, alongside the 1856 Last Island hurricane and Ida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Laura caused at least $19 billion in damage and 77 deaths.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] September was the most active month on record in the Atlantic, with ten named storms.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Slow-moving Hurricane Sally impacted the United States Gulf Coast, causing severe flooding.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The Greek alphabet was used for only the second and final time, starting on September 17 with Subtropical Storm Alpha, which made landfall in Portugal on the following day.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Hurricane Zeta struck Louisiana on October 28, becoming the fourth named storm of the season to make landfall in the state, tying the record set in 2002.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Zeta also struck the United States later in the calendar year than any major hurricane on record.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] On the last day of October, Hurricane Eta formed and made landfall in Nicaragua at Category 4 strength on November 3.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Eta ultimately led to the deaths of at least 175 people and caused $8.3 billion in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Then, on November 10, Tropical Storm Theta became the record-breaking 29th named storm of the season and, three days later, Hurricane Iota formed in the Caribbean.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Iota rapidly intensified into a high-end Category 4 hurricane, which also made 2020 the only recorded season with two major hurricanes in November.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Iota ultimately made landfall in the same general area of Nicaragua that Eta had just weeks earlier and caused catastrophic damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Overall, the tropical cyclones of the 2020 Atlantic hurricane season collectively caused at least 432 deaths and over $55.4 billion in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] All forecasting agencies predicted above-average activity, some well-above-average, citing factors such as the expectation of low wind shear, abnormally warm sea surface temperatures, and a neutral El Niño–Southern Oscillation or La Niña.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Climate change likely played a role in the record-breaking season, with respect to intensity and rainfall.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] However, each prediction, even those issued during the season, underestimated the actual amount of activity.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Early in 2020, officials in the United States expressed concerns the hurricane season could exacerbate the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic for coastal residents due to the potential for a breakdown of safety protocols such as social distancing and stay-at-home orders.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Forecasts of hurricane activity are issued before each hurricane season by noted hurricane experts, such as Philip J.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Klotzbach and his associates at Colorado State University (CSU), and separately by NOAA forecasters.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Klotzbach's team (formerly led by William M.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Gray) defined the average (1981 to 2010) hurricane season as featuring 12.1 tropical storms, 6.4 hurricanes, 2.7 major hurricanes (storms reaching at least Category 3 strength in the Saffir–Simpson scale), and an accumulated cyclone energy (ACE) index of 106 units.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Broadly speaking, ACE is a measure of the power of a tropical or subtropical storm multiplied by the length of time it existed.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] It is only calculated for full advisories on specific tropical and subtropical systems reaching or exceeding wind speeds of 39 mph (63 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] NOAA defines a season as above normal, near normal or below normal by a combination of the number of named storms, the number reaching hurricane strength, the number reaching major hurricane strength, and the ACE Index.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The first seasonal forecast was released on December 19, 2019, by Tropical Storm Risk (TSR), a public consortium consisting of experts on insurance, risk management, and seasonal climate forecasting at University College London, anticipating a slightly above-average hurricane season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This forecast was based on the prediction of near-average trade winds and slightly warmer than normal sea surface temperatures as well as a neutral El Niño–Southern Oscillation (ENSO) phase in the equatorial Pacific.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] In April and May 2020, various agencies issued forecasts for the season, with a hyperactive season predicted by the University of Arizona (UA) and North Carolina State University.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The CSU anticipated heightened probabilities for hurricanes striking the Caribbean and the United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] On May 20, the UK Met Office predicted average activity with 13 tropical storms, 7 hurricanes, and 3 major hurricanes.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] A day later, NOAA released their forecast for an above-normal season, citing the continued ENSO-neutral or even La Niña conditions during the peak of the season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] After the season began, agencies updated their forecasts and generally anticipated an active year.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The Atlantic experienced anomalously low wind shear and surface pressures during the month of July, leading to forecasts for a near-record-breaking season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The CSU and TSR predicted a total of 24 named storms, and NOAA predicted between 19 and 25 named storms.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] This was one of the most active forecasts ever released by NOAA for an Atlantic hurricane season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Overall, the Atlantic tropical cyclones of 2020 collectively resulted in 416 deaths and more than $51.114 billion in damage, making the season one of the costliest on record.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The 2020 Atlantic hurricane season officially began on June 1 and ended on November 30.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] However, tropical cyclogenesis began in the month of May, with tropical storms Arthur and Bertha, marking the sixth consecutive year with an off-season storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] It was the first year with two pre-season storms since 2016, and the first to have two named storms in May since 2012.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The season featured 31 tropical depressions, 30 of which became tropical or subtropical storms.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The latter total surpassed the previous record of 28 set in 2005.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] There were 14 hurricanes, which was the second most for a season, behind only 2005.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Seven of the hurricanes intensified into major hurricanes, tying 2005 for the most in one season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] It was the fifth consecutive Atlantic hurricane season with above average activity, exceeding the previous longest streak of four years between 1998 and 2001.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] A total of 10 tropical cyclones underwent rapid intensification, tying the record set in 1995.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The season extended the warm phase of the Atlantic multidecadal oscillation ongoing since 1995.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The warm AMO tends to produce tropical cyclones that are more intense and have longer durations.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The presence of a La Niña contributed to the unprecedented amount of activity.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Sea surface temperatures across the Atlantic basin were warmer-than-average.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] A strong west African monsoon, favorable wind patterns from Africa, weaker vertical wind shear all aided in the formation of tropical cyclones.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The ACE index for the 2020 Atlantic hurricane season was 180 units, reflecting the season's well-above-average activity.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Climate change likely played a role in the record-breaking season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Matthew Rosencrans, the lead forecaster at the National Weather Service, emphasized that climate change has been linked to the intensity of storms and their slow movements, but not to the amount of activity, which might instead be increasing due to improvements in technology.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The season occurred during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Early in the year, officials in the United States expressed concerns the hurricane season could potentially exacerbate the effects of the pandemic for U.S. coastal residents.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The season featured activity at a record pace.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The third named storm and each one from the fifth onwards formed on an earlier date in the year than the corresponding storm in any other season since reliable records began in 1851.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] In late July, Hanna struck South Texas as the first hurricane of the season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] It was followed by the second hurricane of the season, Isaias, which moved through the Caribbean and eastern United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] July 2020 tied 2005 for the most active July on record in the basin, with five named storms.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Laura and Marco formed toward the end of August, and the former became the first major hurricane of the season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Laura made landfall in southwest Louisiana on August 27 at Category 4 strength with 150 mph (240 km/h) winds.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] September featured the formations of nine named storms, coinciding with the peak of the hurricane season and the development of La Niña conditions.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Hurricane Nana hit Belize in early September.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Paulette was the first hurricane to hit Bermuda since Gonzalo in 2014.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Hurricane Sally hit the Gulf Coast of the United States as a slow-moving Category 2 hurricane.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Teddy, the season's eighth hurricane and second major hurricane formed on September 12, while Vicky formed two days later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] With the formation of the latter, five tropical cyclones were simultaneously active in the Atlantic basin for the first time since 1971.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Alpha developed atypically far east in the Atlantic and became the first tropical cyclone on record to strike Portugal.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Beta's intensification into a tropical storm made September 2020 the most active month on record, with 10 named storms.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Beta went on to make landfall in Texas and impact the Deep South before dissipating, marking an abrupt end to the heavy peak season activity.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] October and November were extremely active, with seven named storms developing, five of which intensified into major hurricanes – more than twice the number recorded during this period in any previous season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Hurricane Gamma hit the Yucatán Peninsula in early October before being absorbed by Hurricane Delta, which hit the region a few days later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Delta struck Louisiana as a hurricane on October 9.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Hurricane Epsilon became a major hurricane near Bermuda.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Toward the end of the month, Hurricane Zeta struck the Yucatán Peninsula and later Louisiana, becoming the latest landfall for a major hurricane in the continental United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] In November, two Category 4 hurricanes hit Nicaragua within a two-week period.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Hurricane Eta moved from Central America to the Greater Antilles and southeastern United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The season's final hurricane was also its strongest.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Hurricane Iota attained maximum sustained winds of 155 mph (249 km/h) and a minimum barometric pressure of 917 mbar (27.1 inHg), before hitting Nicaragua.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The 2020 season became the first with two major hurricanes in the month of November.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] A total of eleven named storms made landfall in the United States, breaking the previous record of nine in 1916.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Six hurricanes hit the country, tying 1886 and 1985 for the most hurricane landfalls in a single season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Eight of the eleven named storms struck the Gulf Coast of the United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Damage throughout the season totaled about $37 billion, including six hurricanes that inflicted at least $1 billion in damage; this was two more than the previous record of four in 2004 and 2005.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Nearly the entire coastline from Texas to Maine was placed under some form of a watch or warning in relation to a tropical system, with only Florida's Jefferson and Wakulla counties being the exception.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Only five counties along the East Coast or Gulf Coast of the United States did not experience tropical storm-force winds.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Louisiana in particular was heavily impacted in 2020, with the state recording four landfalls – three hurricanes and one tropical storm – tying the record set in 2002.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] Outside the United States, a record 13 landfalls occurred.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p01] The two November hurricanes in Central America set back economic development in Honduras by 22 years.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The first tropical depression of the season formed on May 16 about 125 mi (200 km) east of Melbourne, Florida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It quickly intensified into Tropical Storm Arthur, reaching peak winds of 60 mph (95 km/h) and a minimum barometric pressure of 990 mbar (29 inHg) on May 19.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A day later, Arthur interacted with a non-tropical front and became an extratropical cyclone.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The low turned southeast before dissipating near Bermuda a day later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The precursor of Arthur dropped heavy rainfall over portions of the Bahamas, Cuba, and Florida, reaching 9.95 in (253 mm) near Marathon, Florida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Arthur later produced rainfall and storm surge flooding across North Carolina.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Tropical Storm Bertha developed off the northeast coast of Florida on May 27, reaching peak winds of 50 mph (80 km/h) and a central pressure of 1,005 mbar (29.7 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] That day, the storm made landfall near Isle of Palms, South Carolina, and quickly weakened into a tropical depression.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Early on May 28, Bertha transitioned into an extratropical cyclone over western Virginia, before dissipating over the Northern Panhandle of West Virginia.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Florida, the precursor of Bertha brought up to 15 in (380 mm) of rainfall and localized flooding to the Miami area.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] One person drowned in South Carolina due to rip currents generated by the storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Overall, Bertha left at least $133,000 in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On June 1, the remnants of Eastern Pacific Tropical Storm Amanda entered the Bay of Campeche, quickly redeveloping into Tropical Depression Three.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On the next day, it strengthened into Tropical Storm Cristobal, which strengthened while moving southeastward.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm made landfall just west of Ciudad del Carmen at 13:35 UTC on June 3 at its peak intensity of 60 mph (95 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Cristobal weakened into a tropical depression over land, but restrengthened as it moved back over the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Cristobal dropped rainfall throughout the Yucatán Peninsula, reaching 9.6 in (243 mm).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Three people died in Mexico due to the storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In El Salvador, a mudslide caused seven people to go missing.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Once back over water, Cristobal reattained winds of 60 mph (95 km/h) before encountering unfavorable conditions.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Late on June 7, the storm moved ashore southeastern Louisiana, and weakened to a tropical depression as it continued northward.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Cristobal became an extratropical low on June 10 over Iowa, and lasted two more days before dissipating over the Hudson Bay.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Cristobal killed three people in the United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Overall damage was estimated at US$665 million.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Around June 17, an area of disturbed weather developed just north of the Bahamas after part of a tropical wave and an upper-level trough interacted.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The disturbance moved north and organized into a low-pressure area early on June 22.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Shortly thereafter, the low became a subtropical depression about 405 mi (650 km) east-southeast of Cape Cod, Massachusetts.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Mid-level dry air and sea surface temperatures that were only marginally favorable resulted in very little strengthening on June 22.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] However, after moving east-northeastward and away from an upper low, the cyclone developed more deep convection and intensified into Subtropical Storm Dolly by 06:00 UTC on June 23.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] About six hours later, Dolly transitioned into a tropical cyclone and peaked with sustained winds of 45 mph (72 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 1,000 mbar (30 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] However, convection rapidly diminished after Dolly moved north of the Gulf Stream and encountered drier air.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Early on June 24, Dolly degenerated into a remnant low about 200 mi (320 km) south of Sable Island.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The remnant low continued northeastward and dissipated south of Newfoundland early the next day.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A weak frontal system led to the development of a tropical depression on July 4, located about 290 mi (465 km) west-southwest of Bermuda.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The depression passed about 70 mi (110 km) northwest of Bermuda around 08:00 UTC on July 5, producing wind gusts of 43 mph (68 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving northeastward, the depression strengthened into Tropical Storm Edouard on July 6, reaching peak winds of 45 mph (72 km/h) and a minimum barometric pressure of 1,005 mbar (29.7 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Soon after, Edouard merged with an approaching frontal system, which continued across the Atlantic Ocean, eventually moving across Ireland and Great Britain.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Edouard's extratropical remnants brought rainfall to western Europe.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The same trough that produced Tropical Storm Edouard also produced an area of thunderstorms over the northern Gulf of Mexico on July 5.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] After moving across the southeastern United States, the system developed into Tropical Storm Fay on July 9 near Cape Hatteras, North Carolina.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving northward, the storm reached peak winds of 60 mph (95 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 998 mbar (29.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] At 20:00 UTC that day, Fay made landfall near Atlantic City, New Jersey, with winds of 50 mph (80 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It quickly lost intensity inland, degenerating into a remnant low while over southeastern New York and later being absorbed into a larger mid-latitude low over southeastern Canada.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Fay directly caused the deaths of two people, who drowned due to rip currents; four others drowned due to the residual high surf conditions after Fay had passed by.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Overall, damage from the storm in the Northeastern United States totaled at least $350 million.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] New Jersey experienced some of the worst impacts from Fay.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Heavy rainfall caused flooding in several Jersey Shore towns and resulted in closures along many roadways, including the New Jersey Turnpike.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Wind gusts up to 54 mph (87 km/h) left at least 10,000 people in the state without electricity.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A dry, thermal low-pressure area merged with a tropical wave just offshore the west coast of Africa on July 15.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving westward, the system developed into a tropical depression late on July 21 about 1,440 mi (2,315 km) east of the Windward Islands.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] With light wind shear warm waters, the depression intensified into Tropical Storm Gonzalo, reaching peak winds of 65 mph (105 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 997 mbar (29.4 inHg) at 06:00 UTC on July 23.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Dry air from the Saharan Air Layer significantly disrupted the thunderstorms, while stronger wind shear caused weakening.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Gonzalo fell to tropical depression status before making landfall on Trinidad on July 25.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The system degenerated into a trough early the next day near the coast of Venezuela.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm brought stormy weather to Trinidad and Tobago and parts of southern Grenada.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Only two reports of wind damage were received: a fallen tree on a health facility in Les Coteaux and a damaged bus stop roof in Argyle.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical wave moved through Florida into the Gulf of Mexico, leading to the formation of a tropical depression at 00:00 UTC on July 23 about 235 mi (380 km) south-southeast of Louisiana.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving to the west-northwest, the depression soon intensified into Tropical Storm Hanna, developing an eye.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Hanna reached hurricane status on July 25, reaching peak winds of 90 mph (140 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 973 mbar (28.7 inHg) before making landfall on Padre Island, Texas, and later the Kenedy County mainland.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The system rapidly weakened after moving inland, dropping to tropical depression status at 18:00 UTC on July 26 near Monterrey, Nuevo León, and then dissipating shortly thereafter.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Walton County, Florida, a 33-year-old man drowned in rip currents while rescuing his son.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Hanna brought storm surge flooding, destructive winds, torrential rainfall, flash flooding across South Texas.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm destroyed several mobile homes, deroofed many poorly built structures, and left around 200,000 homes in Cameron and Hidalgo counties combined without power.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In the United States, Hanna caused about $1.2 billion in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Mexico, heavy rain fell in Coahuila, Nuevo León, and Tamaulipas.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The cyclone directly caused four deaths in Mexico and caused approximately $100 million in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical wave moved across the Atlantic toward the end of July, leading to the development of Tropical Storm Isaias on July 30 in the eastern Caribbean Sea.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving northwestward, Isaias struck the Dominican Republic and later the Bahamas as it intensified into a hurricane.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Curving to the north, Isaias weakened to tropical storm status, but re-intensified back into a hurricane on August 3.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] At 03:10 UTC the next day, Isaias made landfall in Ocean Isle Beach, North Carolina, with sustained winds of 90 mph (140 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It soon weakened into a tropical storm as it passed over the Mid-Atlantic states, before transitioning to an extratropical low around 00:00 UTC on August 5 while situated over central Vermont, and dissipating several hours later over Quebec.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Isaias caused 17 deaths across the Greater Antilles and eastern United States: 14 in the continental United States, 2 in the Dominican Republic, and 1 in Puerto Rico.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Isaias caused devastating flooding and wind damage in Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In the United States, Isaias produced an outbreak of 39 tornadoes, including an EF3 tornado in North Carolina that killed two people.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Strong winds, storm surge, and many tornadoes left significant damage in the Northeastern United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Almost 3 million people were without electricity at the height of the storm.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On July 28, a tropical wave exited western Africa, which developed a low-pressure area that moved northward around an upper-level low.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The system organized into Tropical Depression Ten on July 31 about 230 mi (370 km) east-southeast of the easternmost Cabo Verde Islands.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Although scatterometer data suggested the possibility of gale-force winds within the thunderstorms, the NHC assessed the depression to have peaked with winds of 35 mph (55 km/h) and a pressure of 1008 mbar (29.77 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The depression weakened due to a combination of decreasing sea surface temperatures and dry air, degenerating into a remnant low on August 1, and dissipating a day later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In early August, a tropical wave moved across the tropical Atlantic, leading to the formation of Tropical Depression Eleven at 06:00 UTC on August 11 about 920 mi (1,480 km) west-southwest of the Cabo Verde Islands.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Dry air and wind shear prevented further strengthening at first, but after a drop in shear, the depression became Tropical Storm Josephine at 12:00 UTC on August 13, with winds of 45 mph (70 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Continued wind shear caused the storm to fluctuate in intensity, and Josephine weakened to a tropical depression on August 16 while passing north of the Leeward Islands.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Soon thereafter, the system degenerated into a trough of low pressure.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A mesoscale convective system moved offshore of South Carolina and Georgia early on August 11, which became better organized as it moved up the coast.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The system developed into Tropical Storm Kyle around 12:00 UTC on August 14, about 105 mi (170 km) east-northeast of Duck, North Carolina.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It moved quickly east-northwestward, reaching a peak intensity on August 15 with peak winds of 50 mph (80 km/h) and a minimum pressure at 1,000 mbar (30 inHg) while located about 230 mi (370 km) southeast of Cape Cod, Massachusetts.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Kyle subsequently weakened due to wind shear, and it became an extratropical cyclone early on August 16, soon after dissipating within the front.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Several days later, extratropical European windstorm Ellen, which contained remnants of Tropical Storm Kyle, brought hurricane-force winds to the Republic of Ireland and the United Kingdom.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On August 20, a tropical depression formed in the open Atlantic Ocean, which quickly intensified into Tropical Storm Laura.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Wind shear prohibited further intensification as the storm moved across the northern Leeward Islands, the Dominican Republic, and later Cuba.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Laura entered the Gulf of Mexico on August 25, quickly becoming a hurricane, and subsequently underwent rapid intensification as it moved toward Louisiana.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] At 00:00 UTC on August 27, Laura reached its peak intensity with maximum sustained winds of 150 mph (240 km/h) and minimum pressure 937 mbar (27.7 inHg) while located just offshore Louisiana, making it a Category 4 hurricane.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Shortly thereafter, Laura made its final landfall near Cameron, Louisiana, at 06:00 UTC, becoming the strongest Louisiana-landfalling tropical cyclone in terms of wind speed since the 1856 Last Island hurricane.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Laura weakened over land, dropping to tropical depression status over Arkansas by August 28.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The deteriorating system turned northeastward and degenerated into a remnant low over northern Kentucky on August 29, which was soon absorbed by another low near the Great Lakes region.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] As Laura passed through the Northern Leeward Islands, it brought heavy rainfall to Guadeloupe and Dominica, and prompted the closing of all ports in the British Virgin Islands.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm produced heavy downpours upon Puerto Rico and Hispaniola.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm left extensive damage in Louisiana, especially in the southwest region of the state.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Storm surge penetrated up to nearly 35 mi (55 km) inland, while Creole and Grand Chenier were inundated with coastal floodwaters ranging from 12 to 18 ft (3.7 to 5.5 m) above ground, sweeping away structures in Cameron Parish.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Wind gusts reached up to 153 mph (246 km/h) at Holly Beach, resulting in catastrophic wind damage in Calcasieu and Cameron parishes.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Outside of the two parishes, Beauregard and Vernon parishes were next hardest hit, with the core of the storm passing directly over.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Several other parishes reported damage to homes and buildings due to strong winds or falling trees.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Laura destroyed approximately 10,000 homes and damaged over 130,000 others in the state.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage in Louisiana alone totaled about $17.5 billion.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Texas was second hardest hit by the storm, with high winds downing many power lines, power poles, and trees in the eastern part of the state, while some counties reported damage to businesses and homes.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Laura produced 16 tornadoes in the United States, the most significant of them being an EF2 tornado in Randolph County, Arkansas.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Altogether, there were 81 storm related deaths.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Of these, 47 were direct deaths associated with Laura, including 31 in Haiti, 9 in the Dominican Republic, and 7 in the United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] There were also 34 indirect deaths, all of them in the United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Tropical Depression Fourteen developed on August 21 from a tropical wave near the coasts of Nicaragua and Honduras.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The system moved northwestward and intensified, becoming Tropical Storm Marco around 00:00 UTC on August 22, as it moved over the northwestern Caribbean.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm strengthened further as it moved through the Yucatán Channel.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Rainfall in western Cuba reached 5.72 in (145 mm) at Cape San Antonio, causing flash flooding.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Marco became a hurricane on August 23 in the southeastern Gulf of Mexico, with maximum sustained winds of 75 mph (120 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 991 mbar (29.3 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Stronger wind shear caused Marco to weaken to a tropical storm on August 24 as it was approaching the coast of Louisiana.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm turned westward and avoided moving ashore, degenerating into a remnant low on August 25 without making landfall.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Heavy rains fell along parts of the Gulf Coast of the United States between Florida and Mississippi, with up to 13.17 in (335 mm) of precipitation near Apalachicola, Florida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Floodwaters inundated many streets in Panama City Beach.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Overall, Marco left approximately $35 million in damage throughout its path.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A trough exited the Southeastern United States on August 29 into the western Atlantic, which produced a low-pressure area northeast of Florida on August 30.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Drifting over the Gulf Stream, the low organized into a tropical depression on August 31 while situated about 150 mi (240 km) south-southeast of Wilmington, North Carolina.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Despite dry air and wind shear, the depression strengthened into Tropical Storm Omar around 12:00 UTC on September 1, with peak winds of 40 mph (65 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 1003 mbar (29.6 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Continued wind shear prevented strengthening, and Omar weakened to a tropical depression early on September 3.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Turning to the north, Omar degenerated into a remnant low about 575 mi (925 km) northeast of Bermuda late on September 5, which was absorbed by a frontal system on the following day.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Toward the end of August, a tropical wave moved through the Caribbean Sea, with a concentrated area of convection.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 1, Tropical Storm Nana developed about 180 mi (290 km) southeast of Kingston, Jamaica.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Despite the presence of wind shear, the storm was able to intensify, becoming a hurricane early on September 3 near the coast of Belize.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] At that time, Nana had maximum sustained winds of 75 mph (120 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 994 mbar (29.4 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Soon after, the hurricane made landfall about 50 mi (80 km) south of Belize City, and it rapidly weakened over land, dissipating on September 4.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane caused more than US$20 million in damage in Belize.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The winds destroyed crops and caused coastal flooding.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Heavy amounts of precipitation also occurred in northern Guatemala and southeastern Mexico.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The remnants later regenerated into Tropical Storm Julio in the eastern Pacific on September 5.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Tropical Depression Seventeen developed on September 7 from a tropical wave, roughly 1,150 mi (1,850 km) west of the Cabo Verde Islands.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving west-northwestward, it quickly intensified into Tropical Storm Paulette.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Wind shear impeded the storm's development, but Paulette was able to strengthen into a hurricane early on September 13, about 415 mi (670 km) southeast of Bermuda.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It turned northward and made landfall on Bermuda at 08:50 UTC on September 14 with winds of 100 mph (160 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm reached its peak intensity later that day, with maximum sustained winds of 105 mph (169 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 965 mbar (28.5 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Paulette accelerated northeastward and weakened, becoming an extratropical cyclone on September 16 to the southeast of Newfoundland.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] After gradually weakening over the following few days and slowly curving southward, the extratropical cyclone started regenerating convection, and Paulette became a tropical storm again on September 20 about 230 mi (370 km) south-southwest of the Azores.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] After reaching a secondary peak of 60 mph (95 km/h), Paulette became post-tropical on September 23, which continued to meander for several days without redevelopment.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The low degenerated into a trough late on September 28.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Paulette caused two fatalities and one injury, due to rip currents along the east coast of the United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Paulette produced hurricane-force winds on Bermuda, with sustained winds reaching 79 mph (127 km/h) at Pearl Island and surface-level gusts reaching 97 mph (156 km/h) at L.F.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane led to 25,000 power outages, or about 70 percent of electrical customers on the island.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage on Bermuda totaled approximately $50 million.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical wave exited western Africa on September 6, leading to the formation of Tropical Depression Eighteen on September 7 about 200 mi (320 km) east of Cabo Verde.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It soon strengthened into Tropical Storm Rene, which hit Boa Vista Island around 00:00 UTC on September 8 with sustained winds of 40 mph (65 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm brought gusty winds and heavy rains to Cabo Verde.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Rene weakened to a tropical depression several hours, but re-strengthened into a tropical storm early on September 9.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] At 12:00 UTC on September 10, Rene peaked with sustained winds of 45 mph (72 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 1,001 mbar (29.6 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Dry air caused thunderstorms to diminish, and Rene weakened to a tropical depression on September 12.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Strong westerly shear caused further weakening, with Rene degenerating into a trough on September 14 about 1,035 mi (1,665 km) northeast of the Leeward Islands.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The remnants turned southwestward and dissipated a few days later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In early September, a trough developed over the western Atlantic, leading to the formation of Tropical Depression Nineteen on September 11 over the Bahamas.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving westward, the depression made landfall near Cutler Bay, Florida, early on September 12.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] While moving over the Everglades, the depression strengthened into Tropical Storm Sally, which soon emerged into the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Sally moved northwestward, intensifying into a hurricane on September 14.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane slowed to a crawl while turning north-northeastward, becoming a high-end Category 2 hurricane by 06:00 UTC September 16.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] At around 09:45 UTC that day, the system made landfall at peak intensity near Gulf Shores, Alabama, with maximum sustained winds of 110 mph (175 km/h) and a minimum central pressure of 965 mbar (28.5 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Sally quickly weakened over land, becoming an extratropical low on September 17, which was later absorbed within a cold front.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Across the United States, Sally was responsible for nine fatalities and approximately $7.3 billion in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm caused widespread power outages affecting at least 560,000 people.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In its early stages, Sally dropped heavy rainfall in South Florida, causing flooding.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane destroyed approximately 50 structures in the Florida Panhandle, while thousands of others in Escambia and Santa Rosa counties suffered damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] There were 23 tornadoes reported across the Southeastern United States while Sally was a tropical cyclone.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical wave emerged from the west coast of Africa on September 10, leading to the formation of a tropical depression two days later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 14 it intensified into Tropical Storm Teddy, which continued to strengthen while moving across the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Teddy became a hurricane on September 16, and two days later it reached its peak intensity with maximum sustained winds of 140 mph (230 km/h) and a minimum barometric pressure of 945 mbar (27.9 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Teddy weakened due to an eyewall replacement cycle and increased wind shear.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The cyclone passed about 230 mi (370 km) east of Bermuda on September 21 as it turned north-northeastward.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Teddy interacted with an approaching trough, causing the hurricane to re-intensify and become more asymmetric.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane became an extratropical cyclone on September 23, and soon after moved ashore Atlantic Canada near Ecum Secum, Nova Scotia, with sustained winds of 65 mph (105 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The system was eventually absorbed by a larger non-tropical low early on September 24 near eastern Labrador.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Hurricane Teddy generated large ocean swells which spread along much of the U.S.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Atlantic coast and from the northern Caribbean to Bermuda, killing three people.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Abnormally high tides also caused coastal flooding in Charleston, South Carolina, and the Outer Banks of North Carolina.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] About 220 households lost power in Bermuda.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The extratropical remnants of Teddy generated wind gusts up to 90 mph (145 km/h) in Nova Scotia.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Approximately 18,000 customers throughout the Atlantic Canada region lost electricity.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] There were also isolated reports of minor flooding.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage from Teddy in all areas impacted totaled roughly $35 million.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Early on September 11, a tropical wave exited western Africa.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The next day, the system moved across the Cabo Verde Islands, producing flooding that killed one person in Praia.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The city recorded 5 in (88 mm) of precipitation over 24 hours.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Flooding blocked several roads and damaged automobiles, bridges, buildings, and farmland.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Continuing to the northwest, the system developed into Tropical Depression Twenty-One on September 14, which quickly strengthened into Tropical Storm Vicky.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Despite strong wind shear partially caused by Hurricane Teddy's outflow, Vicky intensified to reach peak winds of 50 mph (80 km/h) and a pressure of 1,001 mbar (29.6 inHg) on September 15.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Continued wind shear caused Vicky to weaken, and the storm dissipated on September 17.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] An area of disturbed weather was first observed on September 5, stretching from the western Caribbean to offshore the Southeastern United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The influence of nearby Hurricane Sally initially prevented further development.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A day after that hurricane moved ashore, Tropical Depression Twenty-Two developed in the Gulf of Mexico on September 17, located about 350 mi (565 km) south-southeast of Brownsville, Texas.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 18, the depression became Tropical Storm Beta, reaching peak winds of 65 mph (105 km/h) two days later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm slowed its movement, resulting in upwelling, which caused weakening.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Beta made landfall early on September 22 near Port O'Connor, Texas, soon weakening and becoming extratropical.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The low dissipated over northeastern Alabama early on September 25.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm dropped heavy rainfall, with a total of 15.77 in (401 mm) in Brookside Village, Texas.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The rains led to flooding across the Greater Houston metropolitan area, resulting in a drowning death in Brays Bayou.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Throughout the United States, Beta caused approximately $225 million in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Rising floodwaters necessitated more than 100 high-water rescues and the closures of several highways and interstates in the area.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical wave exited western Africa on September 13.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] After a well-defined circulation formed within an area of deep convection, the system developed into Tropical Storm Wilfred late on September 17 while situated about 345 mi (555 km) southwest of Cabo Verde.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It only reached peak winds of 40 mph (65 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 1,006 mbar (29.7 inHg), before weakening due to dry air and wind shear.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Wilfred weakened to a tropical depression on September 20, and degenerated into an open trough the next day about 920 mi (1,480 km) east of the northern Leeward Islands.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A large extratropical low developed over the northeast Atlantic Ocean on September 14, which moved south-southeastward.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The wind field contracted as thunderstorms formed over the circulation.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On September 17, the system developed into Subtropical Storm Alpha roughly 405 mi (650 km) east of the Azores.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Alpha strengthened to attain winds of 50 mph (80 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 996 mbar (29.4 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] At 18:40 UTC on September 18, the cyclone made landfall about 10 mi (15 km) south of Figueira da Foz, Portugal.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Alpha caused more than $1 million in damage, and resulted in one fatality due to a collapsed roof in Calzadilla, Spain.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm also spawned at least two tornadoes, both rated EF1 on the Enhanced Fujita scale.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Spain, the front associated with Alpha caused a train to derail in Madrid, while thunderstorms on Ons Island caused a forest fire.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical depression developed on October 2 in the northwestern Caribbean Sea, about 300 mi (485 km) southeast of the Yucatán peninsula.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It quickly intensified into Tropical Storm Gamma and intensified further into a hurricane, reaching winds of 75 mph (120 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 978 mbar (28.9 inHg) as it made landfall near Tulum, Quintana Roo on October 3.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Gamma weakened over land and emerged into the southern Gulf of Mexico, encountering wind shear and dry air.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It weakened into a tropical depression before making another landfall on the Yucatán peninsula on October 6, near San Felipe, Yucatán.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Soon after, Gamma was absorbed by approaching Hurricane Delta.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Hurricane Gamma caused at least six deaths in Mexico, while damage was estimated at $100 million.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Precipitation peaked at 15.11 in (384 mm) in Tizimin.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm produced strong winds, heavy rainfall, flash flooding, landslides, and mudslides in the region.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Gamma's outerbands also produced heavy rainfall in the Cayman Islands, Cuba, and Florida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In early October, a tropical wave moved across the Caribbean, leading to the formation of Tropical Depression Twenty-Six on October 4 to the southeast of Jamaica.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It intensified into Tropical Storm Delta, and soon began a period of rapid intensification, as convection became more symmetrical.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Delta became a hurricane at 00:00 October 6, and later that day peaked as a Category 4 hurricane with maximum winds of 140 mph (230 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 953 mbar (28.1 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] This period of rapid intensification resulted in a 105 mph (170 km/h) increase in winds over a 36-hour period, caused by a combination of extremely warm ocean water temperatures, low wind shear, and sufficient moisture.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] However, an increase in wind shear caused Delta to weaken, and on October 7 the hurricane struck the eastern Mexican state of Quintana Roo as a Category 2 hurricane with sustained winds of 105 mph (170 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Delta weakened over land, but re-intensified over the Gulf of Mexico, reaching a secondary peak of 120 mph (195 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 953 mbar (28.1 inHg) on October 9.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Later that day, unfavorable conditions caused the hurricane to weaken, and Delta made its final landfall near Creole, Louisiana, with winds of 100 mph (160 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The landfall was about 10 mi (15 km) east of where Hurricane Laura's eye crossed the coast on August 27.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Inland, Delta weakened to tropical storm, and later became extratropical over Mississippi late on October 10.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The system degenerated into a trough over Tennessee two days later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Hurricane Delta caused six fatalities, two each in the Yucatán, Louisiana, and Florida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Mexico, damage in Mexico totaled approximately $185 million, with power outages, uprooted trees, and flooding.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage from Delta in the United States reached $2.9 billion.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane and its remnants produced heavy rain, strong winds, storm surge, and tornadoes across much of the Southeastern United States.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Louisiana, strong winds generated by Delta caused additional damage to structures that were impacted by Laura, while debris remaining from Hurricane Laura were scattered across roadways and drains.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] However, much of the damage in the state was caused by flooding, with 17.57 in (446 mm) of rainfall at LeBleu Settlement.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Floodwaters entered several homes in Baton Rouge and Calcasieu.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Mississippi, roughly 100,000 businesses and homes lost electricity after rainfall and tropical storm-force wind gusts uprooted trees.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A non-tropical low formed on October 16 to the east of Bermuda.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving southward over warmer waters, the system developed enough organized convection to become Tropical Depression Twenty-Seven on October 19.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It soon intensified into Tropical Storm Epsilon as it executed a small counter-clockwise loop.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Dry air and wind shear affected the storm at first, but Epsilon strengthened once the shear subsided and it began a northwest track.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm became a hurricane on October 21, and a day later Epsilon reached maximum sustained winds of 115 mph (185 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 952 mbar (28.1 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Epsilon marked the farthest east that a major hurricane had been observed after October 20.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It soon weakened, passing about 185 mi (300 km) to the east of Bermuda as a minimal hurricane on October 23.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] After turning to the northeast, Epsilon weakened to a tropical storm, becoming an extratropical storm on October 26 about 565 mi (910 km) east of Cape Race, Newfoundland.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Epsilon's remnants were later absorbed into a deep extratropical low southwest of Iceland.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane caused one direct death; a 27-year-old man drowned in Epsilon-induced rip currents in Daytona Beach, Florida.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane also generated large sea swells from Bermuda to the Bahamas, the Greater Antilles, and the Leeward Islands.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Rainfall on the island as the storm passed by amounted to less than 1 in (25 mm); winds at Bermuda's airport gusted near tropical storm-force, with a peak wind gust of 38 mph (61 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The trailing weather fronts associated with this low produced waves up to 98 ft (30 m) on the coast of Ireland on October 28.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The interaction of a tropical wave and a midlevel trough led to the formation of Tropical Depression Twenty-Eight on October 24 near Grand Cayman.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It quickly intensified into Tropical Storm Zeta, and reached hurricane status on October 26.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] That day, Zeta made landfall near Ciudad Chemuyil, Quintana Roo, with winds of 85 mph (135 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] After weakening to a tropical storm inland, Zeta moved offshore of the northern coast of the Yucatán Peninsula about 11 hours later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On October 28, it reattained hurricane status as it turned northward.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Zeta peaked later that day at 21:00 UTC when it became a Category 3 major hurricane with maximum sustained winds of 115 mph (185 km/h) and a minimum barometric pressure of 970 mbar (29 inHg), as it made its second landfall near Cocodrie, Louisiana.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Zeta steadily lost strength after landfall, weakening to a tropical storm over Alabama at 06:00 UTC on October 29, before transitioning into a post-tropical cyclone over central Virginia by 18:00 UTC that day, while moving rapidly northeastward.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Early on October 30, Zeta's remnants dissipated east of the mid-Atlantic U.S. coast.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Heavy rain in Jamaica caused a landslide that killed two people after demolishing a home in Saint Andrew Parish.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Zeta left roughly $15 million in damage on the island.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Strong winds and rain caused flooding and damaged infrastructure in Mexico's Yucatán Peninsula.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] There were seven related deaths in the United States: three in Georgia; two in Mississippi; and one each in Louisiana and Mississippi.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage within the United States totaled $4.4 billion.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Zeta knocked out power to more than 2.6 million homes and businesses across the Southeastern United States; it also disrupted 2020 election early voting in several states.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Louisiana, wind gusts reached 110 mph (180 km/h) at Golden Meadow, Louisiana.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Zeta had damaging effects as far northeast as Virginia, while its remnants produced snow across parts of New England.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Toward the end of October, a tropical wave moved across the Caribbean Sea, leading to the formation of Tropical Depression Twenty-Nine late on October 31.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Moving westward, it strengthened into Tropical Storm Eta and continued to intensify rapidly as it approached Central America.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Late on November 2, Eta reached peak intensity with sustained maximum winds of 150 mph (240 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 922 mbar (27.2 inHg) at 06:00 UTC on November 3.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Later that day, at 21:00 UTC, it made landfall south-southwest of Puerto Cabezas, Nicaragua, with winds of 140 mph (225 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Over land, Eta rapidly weakened to a tropical depression and lost its surface circulation, although its mid-level center remained present.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On November 6, the system redeveloped into a tropical depression, which again became a tropical storm as it moved to the northeast.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Eta struck eastern Cuba as it curved back to the northwest, moving across the Florida Keys into the Gulf of Mexico on November 9.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm briefly re-strengthened into a hurricane southwest of Florida on November 11, before weakening back to tropical storm strength.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] It then turned northeastward and made its final landfall near Cedar Key, Florida, at 09:00 UTC on November 12, with winds of 50 mph (80 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm weakened over land and emerged over the Atlantic Ocean, becoming extratropical on November 13.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Overall, more than 210 fatalities across Central America were attributed to the storm, including 74 in Honduras, 60 in Guatemala, 27 in Mexico, 19 in Panama, 10 in the United States, two each in Nicaragua and Costa Rica, and one in El Salvador.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage in Central America reached approximately $6.8 billion.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The intense wind and rain generated by Eta caused flooding and landslides, resulting in crop losses, plus the destruction of roads, bridges, power lines and houses throughout Central America.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm damaged or demolished at least 6,900 homes, 45 schools, 16 healthcare facilities, and some 560 mi (900 km) of bridges and roadways throughout Nicaragua.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Eta also damaged hundreds of dwellings to some degree in both Guatemala and Honduras.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Washed-out bridges and roads isolated more than 40 communities in the latter.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In Guatemala, flooding also ruined more than 290,000 acres (119,000 ha) of crops.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Mexico suffered significant impacts as well, with thousands of homes damaged in Chiapas and Tabasco.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Relief efforts were severely hampered when, just two weeks later, Hurricane Iota made landfall approximately 15 miles (24 km) south of where Eta moved ashore.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Eta bought heavy rainfall and gusty winds to the Cayman Islands and Cuba, the latter of which was already dealing with overflowing rivers that prompted the evacuations of 25,000 people.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm caused roughly $1.5 billion in damage in the United States, mostly related to flooding.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On November 6, the NHC began monitoring a non-tropical area of disturbed weather in the central Atlantic for possible gradual subtropical development.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A non-tropical low subsequently formed about 1,300 mi (2,100 km) west-southwest of the Azores on November 8.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The system became better organized as it began to detach from a frontal boundary during the following day.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] At 00:00 UTC on November 10, it developed into Subtropical Storm Theta.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] By 18:00 UTC that afternoon, the storm had transitioned into a tropical storm; it simultaneously attained what would be its peak intensity, with maximum winds of 70 mph (110 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 987 mbar (29.1 inHg).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] By the following morning, the effects of strong southwesterly shear had weakened Theta somewhat, though it soon began to regain some strength, and by 00:00 UTC on November 12, re-intensified to its earlier peak.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Steady weakening occurred on November 13–14, as the storm experienced strong northerly vertical shear.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] By 06:00 UTC on November 15, Theta had weakened to a tropical depression about 120 mi (195 km) southwest of Madeira Island, and it degenerated to a remnant low six hours later.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A tropical wave exited the west coast of Africa on October 30, which eventually led to the formation of Tropical Depression Thirty-One on November 13.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The depression intensified into Tropical Storm Iota as it moved westward through an area of warm waters and low wind shear.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Iota rapidly intensified, becoming a hurricane on November 15, and reaching its peak intensity a day later with maximum winds of 155 mph (250 km/h) and a minimum pressure of 917 mbar (27.1 inHg), while located just 23 mi (37 km) northwest of Providencia Island.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The hurricane weakened slightly before making landfall at 03:40 UTC on November 17 in eastern Nicaragua with sustained winds of 145 mph (235 km/h).
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Iota rapidly weakened over land, dissipating late on November 18 over El Salvador.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Its landfall location was approximately 15 mi (25 km) south of where Eta made landfall on November 3.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Hurricane Iota caused at least 84 deaths along its path and resulted in about $1.4 billion in damage.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The storm first affected Venezuela, damaging homes in Falcón state.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Iota demolished approximately 98 percent of the infrastructure on Providencia Island, while also damaging hundreds of houses.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Most of the damage occurred in Nicaragua and Honduras.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] In the former, wind damage was limited to an extent due to the recent passage of Hurricane Eta.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] However, the cyclone knocked down many electrical poles and deroofed many homes and a makeshift hospital in the Puerto Cabezas area.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Heavy rainfall, combined with already saturated soil due to Eta, caused widespread flooding and mudslides.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Heavy precipitation resulted in flooding and mudslides in Honduras, especially close to or north of Iota's path, completely destroying numerous homes.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Mexico also reported extensive impacts from the storm, especially in Chiapas, Tabasco, and Veracruz.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Floodwaters and mudslides damaged almost 59,000 homes and left 135 communities isolated.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The following list of names was used for named storms that formed in the North Atlantic in 2020.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] This was the same list used for the 2014 season, as no names were retired from that year.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The names *Isaias* and *Paulette*, which replaced *Ike* and *Paloma* after 2008, along with *Rene*, *Sally*, *Teddy*, *Vicky*, and *Wilfred* from the regular list were used for the first time in 2020, as were the auxiliary list Greek letters *Eta*, *Theta*, and *Iota*.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] This was the second Atlantic hurricane season to exhaust the designated list of 21 storm names, and to utilize the auxiliary list, along with 2005.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] On March 17, 2021, during the joint 42nd and 43rd Sessions of the RA IV Hurricane Committee, the World Meteorological Organization (WMO) retired the name *Laura*, meaning it will not be used again in the North Atlantic basin.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] *Laura* was replaced with *Leah*, which will first appear on the 2026 season list.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The Greek letters *Eta* and *Iota* were also retired.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The WMO also decided to discontinue use of the Greek alphabet as an auxiliary list.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] A new supplemental list consisting of 21 given names was put in its place beginning with the 2021 season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] The WMO did not retire the names of several 2020 hurricanes that caused extensive damage, specifically: *Isaias*, *Sally*, *Delta* and *Zeta*.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] This made Sally, the most destructive of the four, with a damage total of around $7.3 billion (2020 USD), the most expensive non-retired North Atlantic hurricane on record.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] This is a table of all of the tropical cyclones that formed in the 2020 Atlantic hurricane season.
[src:greek-alphabet/2020-atlantic-hurricane-season-p02] Damage and deaths include totals while the storm was extratropical, a wave, or a low, and all of the damage figures are in 2020 USD.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] An **abecedarium** (/ˌeɪ.bi.siˈdɛər.i.əm/ *AY-bee-see-DAIR-ee-əm*; also known as an **abecedary**, the **ABCs** or simply an **ABC**) is an inscription consisting of the letters of an alphabet, almost always listed in order.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] Typically, abecedaria (or abecedaries) are practice exercises.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] Runic abecedaria are found both in manuscripts, and rune-row inscriptions, such as the Kylver stone (c.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] They typically begin with ᚠᚢᚦ (**fuþ**), followed by runes that vary based on the writing systems being used, be it Elder Fuþark, Anglo-Frisian Fuþorc, Younger Fuþark or Medieval Fuþork.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] Some abecedaria include obsolete letters that are not otherwise attested in inscriptions.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] For example, abecedaria in the Etruscan alphabet from Marsiliana (the Tuscan town) include the letters B, D, and O, which indicate sounds not present in the Etruscan language and are therefore not found in Etruscan inscriptions.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] Others, such as those known from Safaitic inscriptions, list the letters of the alphabet in different orders, suggesting that the script was casually rather than formally learned.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] Some abecedaria found in the Athenian Agora appear to be deliberately incomplete, consisting of only the first three to six letters of the Greek alphabet, and these may have had a magical or ritual significance.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] A deliberately incomplete abecedarium found at Hymettos in Attica may have been a votive offering.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] Near the beginning of the Christian era, the Latin alphabet had already undergone its principal changes, and had become a definite system.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] The Greek alphabet was growing closer to the Latin alphabet.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] Towards the 8th century of Rome, the letters assumed their artistic forms and lost their older, narrower ones.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] The three letters added by Emperor Claudius have never been found in use in Christian inscriptions.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] The letters fell into disuse after Claudius's death.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] The alphabet used for monumental inscriptions was very different from the cursive.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] The uncial, occurring very rarely on sculptured monuments, and reserved for writing, did not appear until the 4th century.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] The majority of objects bearing the abecedaria are not of Christian origin, with the exception of two vases found at Carthage.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] These objects included tablets used by stone-cutters' apprentices while learning their trade.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] Stones have also been found in the catacombs, bearing the symbols A, B, C, etc.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] These are arranged, sometimes, in combinations which have puzzled scholars.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] One such stone, found in the cemetery of St.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] This can be compared with a denarius of L.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] Children were made to learn the alphabet in pairs of letters, joining the first letter of the alphabet with the last letter (AX), the second letter with the second to last (BV), and so on.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] A stone found at Rome in 1877, and dating from the 6th or 7th century, seems to have been used in a school, as a model for learning the alphabet, and points to the continuance of old methods of teaching.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] An *Abecedary*, a full alphabet carved in stone or written in book form, was historically found in churches, monasteries and other ecclesiastical buildings.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] Abecedaries are generally considered to be medieval teaching aids, particularly for the illiterate.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] The alphabet may have been thought to possess supernatural powers along the lines of the runic alphabet.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] Each letter would have had a symbolic meaning to the devout.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] An example, the first seven letters or so of which were found in 1967, is from the long demolished Church of St Mary of the Grey Friars in Dumfries, Scotland.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] In this case, the letters are inscribed in the Lombardic script of the 1260s and the complete structure would probably have stood near the high altar .
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] One of the oldest examples is now in use as a gravestone in Kilmalkedar, near Dingle, Ireland.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] It has the appearance of a standing stone and is known as the Alphabet Stone, displaying as it does an alphabet dating from early Christian times.
[src:greek-alphabet/abecedarium] Abecedarian psalms and hymns exist, these are compositions like Psalm 119 in Hebrew, and the Akathist hymn in Greek, in which distinct stanzas or verses commence with successive letters of the alphabet.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] 'alphabet') is a writing system in which only consonants are represented by letter signs, leaving the vowels to be inferred by the reader (unless represented otherwise, such as by diacritics).
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] This contrasts with alphabets that provide graphemes for both consonants and vowels.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] The term was introduced in 1990 by Peter T.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] Other terms for the same concept include **partial phonemic script**, **segmentally linear defective phonographic script**, **consonantary**, **consonant writing**, and **consonantal alphabet**.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] According to the formulations of Peter T.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] Daniels, abjads differ from alphabets in that only consonants, not vowels, are represented among the basic graphemes.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] Abjads differ from abugidas, another category defined by Daniels, in that in abjads, the vowel sound is *implied* by phonology, and where vowel marks exist for the system, such as niqqud for Hebrew and ḥarakāt for Arabic, their use is optional and not the dominant (or literate) form.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] Abugidas mark all vowels (other than the "inherent" vowel) with a diacritic, a minor attachment to the letter, a standalone grapheme, or (in Canadian Aboriginal syllabics) by rotation of the letter.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] Some abugidas use a special symbol to *suppress* the inherent vowel so that the consonant alone can be properly represented.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] In a syllabary, a grapheme denotes a complete syllable, that is, either a lone vowel sound or a combination of a vowel sound with one or more consonant sounds.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] The contrast of abjad versus alphabet has been rejected by other scholars because *abjad* is also used as a term for the Arabic numeral system.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] Also, it may be taken as suggesting that consonantal alphabets, in contrast to e.g. the Greek alphabet, were not yet true alphabets.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] Florian Coulmas, a critic of Daniels and of the abjad terminology, argues that this terminology can confuse alphabets with "transcription systems", and that there is no reason to relegate the Hebrew, Aramaic or Phoenician alphabets to second-class status as an "incomplete alphabet".
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] However, Daniels's terminology has found acceptance in the linguistic community.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] The Proto-Sinaitic script represents the earliest-known example of alphabetic writing.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] The Proto-Sinaitic script is thought to represent, or at least indicate the existence of, an early ancestor of the many later Semitic consonantal scripts which continued to develop over time into more abstract, less visually representational forms, including the Phoenician abjad.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] The Phoenician abjad was a radical simplification of phonetic writing.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] Unlike other scripts, such as Mesopotamian cuneiform (logographic and syllabic) and Egyptian hieroglyphs (logographic and consonantal), the Phoenician abjad consisted of only a few dozen symbols.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] During these exchanges, the Phoenician script gave rise to a number of new writing systems, including the widely used Aramaic abjad and the Greek alphabet.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] The Greek alphabet was later developed into several alphabets, including Etruscan, Coptic, Cyrillic, and Latin (via Etruscan), while Aramaic became the ancestor of many abjads and abugidas of Asia, particularly in and around India, Southeast Asia, and Oceania.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] Impure abjads have characters for some vowels, optional vowel diacritics, or both.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] The term pure abjad refers to scripts entirely lacking in vowel indicators.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] This practice was at first rare and limited in scope but became increasingly common and more developed in later times.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] In the 9th century BC the Greeks adapted the Phoenician script for use in their own language.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] The phonetic structure of the Greek language created too many ambiguities when vowels went unrepresented, so the script was modified.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] They did not need letters for the guttural sounds represented by *aleph*, *he*, *heth* or *ayin*, so these symbols were assigned vocalic values.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] The letters *waw* and *yod* were also adapted into vowel signs; along with *he*, these were already used as *matres lectionis* in Phoenician.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] Abugidas developed along a slightly different route.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] The basic consonantal symbol was considered to have an inherent "a" vowel sound.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] Hooks or short lines attached to various parts of the basic letter modify the vowel.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] In this way, the South Arabian abjad evolved into the Geʽez script of Ethiopia between the 5th century BC and the 5th century AD.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] Similarly, the Brāhmī abugida of the Indian subcontinent developed around the 3rd century BC (from the Aramaic abjad, it has been hypothesized).
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] The abjad form of writing is well-adapted to the morphological structure of the Semitic languages it was developed to write.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] This is because words in Semitic languages are formed from a root consisting of (usually) three consonants, the vowels being used to indicate inflectional or derived forms.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] In most cases, the absence of full glyphs for vowels makes the common root clearer, allowing readers to guess the meaning of unfamiliar words from familiar roots (especially in conjunction with context clues) and improving word recognition while reading for practiced readers.
[src:greek-alphabet/abjad] The Hebrew abjad has also been adapted to write Jewish languages like Ladino and Yiddish.
[src:greek-alphabet/ala-lc-romanization] The system is used to represent bibliographic information by North American libraries and the British Library (for acquisitions since 1975) and in publications throughout the English-speaking world.
[src:greek-alphabet/ala-lc-romanization] The Anglo-American Cataloguing Rules require catalogers to romanize access points from their non-Roman originals.
[src:greek-alphabet/ala-lc-romanization] However, as the MARC standards have been expanded to allow records containing Unicode characters, many cataloguers now include bibliographic data in both Roman and original scripts.
[src:greek-alphabet/ala-lc-romanization] The ALA-LC Romanization includes over 70 romanization tables.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "¿ ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: σῶμα *sôma* 'body') and hands (Greek: χείρ *kheír* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives – Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Handshapes – Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Movements – Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks – These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] There are three points – an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** –, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., – or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2–4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:greek-alphabet/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The **Greek alphabet** has been used to write the Greek language since the late 9th or early 8th century BC.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] It was derived from the earlier Phoenician alphabet, and is the earliest known alphabetic script to systematically write vowels as well as consonants.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The Greek alphabet is the ancestor of several scripts, such as the Latin, Gothic, Coptic, and Cyrillic scripts.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Throughout antiquity, Greek had only a single uppercase form of each letter.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] It was written without diacritics and with little punctuation.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] By the 9th century, Byzantine scribes had begun to employ the lowercase form, which they derived from the cursive styles of the uppercase letters.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Sound values and conventional transcriptions for some of the letters differ between Ancient and Modern Greek usage because the pronunciation of Greek has changed significantly between the 5th century BC and the present.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Additionally, Modern and Ancient Greek now use different diacritics, with ancient Greek using the polytonic orthography and modern Greek keeping only the stress accent (acute) and the diaeresis.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Apart from its use in writing the Greek language, in both its ancient and its modern forms, the Greek alphabet today also serves as a source of international technical symbols and labels in many domains of mathematics, science, and other fields.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In both Ancient and Modern Greek, the letters of the Greek alphabet have fairly stable and consistent symbol-to-sound mappings, making pronunciation of words largely predictable.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Ancient Greek spelling was generally near-phonemic.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] For a number of letters, sound values differ considerably between Ancient and Modern Greek, because their pronunciation has followed a set of systematic phonological shifts that affected the language in its post-classical stages.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] These are not the sounds they made in classical Attic Greek.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In classical Attic Greek, these three letters were always aspirated consonants, pronounced exactly like tau, pi, and kappa respectively, only with a blast of air following the actual consonant sound.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The letter Λ is almost universally known today as *lambda* (λάμβδα) except in Modern Greek and in Unicode, where it is *lamda* (λάμδα), and the most common name for it during the Greek Classical Period (510–323 BC) appears to have been *labda* (λάβδα), without the μ.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The letter sigma ⟨Σ⟩ has two different lowercase forms in its standard variant, with ⟨ς⟩ being used in word-final position and ⟨σ⟩ elsewhere.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In some 19th-century typesetting, ⟨ς⟩ was also used word-medially at the end of a compound morpheme, e.g. δυςκατανοήτων, marking the morpheme boundary between δυς-κατανοήτων ('difficult to understand'); modern standard practice is to spell δυσκατανοήτων with a non-final sigma.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The letter omega ⟨ω⟩ is normally taught to English speakers as [oʊ], the long o as in English *go*, in order to more clearly distinguish it from omicron ⟨ο⟩.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] This is not the sound it actually made in classical Attic Greek.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Among consonant letters, all letters that denoted voiced plosive consonants (/b, d, g/) and aspirated plosives (/pʰ, tʰ, kʰ/) in Ancient Greek stand for corresponding fricative sounds in Modern Greek.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Among the vowel letters, Modern Greek sound values reflect the radical simplification of the vowel system of post-classical Greek, merging multiple formerly distinct vowel phonemes into a much smaller number.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] This leads to several groups of vowel letters denoting identical sounds today.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Modern Greek orthography remains true to the historical spellings in most of these cases.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] As a consequence, the spellings of words in Modern Greek are often not predictable from the pronunciation alone, while the reverse mapping, from spelling to pronunciation, is usually regular and predictable.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Modern Greek speakers typically use the same, modern symbol–sound mappings in reading Greek of all historical stages.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In other countries, students of Ancient Greek may use a variety of conventional approximations of the historical sound system in pronouncing Ancient Greek.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Several letter combinations have special conventional sound values different from those of their single components.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Among them are several digraphs of vowel letters that formerly represented diphthongs but are now monophthongized.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In addition to the four mentioned above (⟨ει, οι, υι⟩, pronounced /i/ and ⟨αι⟩, pronounced /e/), there is also ⟨ηι, ωι⟩, and ⟨ου⟩, pronounced /u/.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The Ancient Greek diphthongs ⟨αυ⟩, ⟨ευ⟩ and ⟨ηυ⟩ are pronounced [av], [ev] and [iv] in Modern Greek.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In some environments, they are devoiced to [af], [ef] and [if].
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The Modern Greek consonant combinations ⟨μπ⟩ and ⟨ντ⟩ stand for [b] and [d] (or [mb] and [nd]); ⟨τζ⟩ stands for [d͡z] and ⟨τσ⟩ stands for [t͡s].
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In addition, both in Ancient and Modern Greek, the letter ⟨γ⟩, before another velar consonant, stands for the velar nasal [ŋ]; thus ⟨γγ⟩ and ⟨γκ⟩ are pronounced like English ⟨ng⟩ like in the word finger (not like in the word thing).
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In analogy to ⟨μπ⟩ and ⟨ντ⟩, ⟨γκ⟩ is also used to stand for [g] before vowels [a], [o] and [u], and [ɟ] before [e] and [i].
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] There are also the combinations ⟨γχ⟩ and ⟨γξ⟩.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The smooth breathing marks the absence of an initial /h/.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In the polytonic orthography traditionally used for ancient Greek and katharevousa, the stressed vowel of each word carries one of three accent marks: either the acute accent (ά), the grave accent (ὰ), or the circumflex accent (α̃ or α̑).
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] These signs were originally designed to mark different forms of the phonological pitch accent in Ancient Greek.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] By the time their use became conventional and obligatory in Greek writing, in late antiquity, pitch accent was evolving into a single stress accent, and thus the three signs have not corresponded to a phonological distinction in actual speech ever since.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In addition to the accent marks, every word-initial vowel must carry either of two so-called "breathing marks": the rough breathing (ἁ), marking an /h/ sound at the beginning of a word, or the smooth breathing (ἀ), marking its absence.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The letter rho (ρ), although not a vowel, also carries rough breathing in a word-initial position.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] If a rho was geminated within a word, the first ρ always had the smooth breathing and the second the rough breathing (ῤῥ) leading to the transliteration *rrh*.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The vowel letters ⟨α, η, ω⟩ carry an additional diacritic in certain words, the so-called iota subscript, which has the shape of a small vertical stroke or a miniature ⟨ι⟩ below the letter.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] This iota represents the former offglide of what were originally long diphthongs, ⟨ᾱι, ηι, ωι⟩ (i.e. /aːi, ɛːi, ɔːi/), which became monophthongized during antiquity.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Another diacritic used in Greek is the diaeresis (*¨*), indicating a hiatus.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] This system of diacritics was first developed by the scholar Aristophanes of Byzantium (c.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] 185/180 BC), who worked at the Musaeum in Alexandria during the 3rd century BC.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Aristophanes of Byzantium also was the first to divide poems into lines, rather than writing them like prose, and also introduced a series of signs for textual criticism.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In 1982, a new, simplified orthography, known as "monotonic", was adopted for official use in Modern Greek by the Greek state.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The polytonic system is still conventionally used for writing Ancient Greek, while in some book printing and generally in the usage of conservative writers it can still also be found in use for Modern Greek.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Although it is not a diacritic, the comma has a similar function as a silent letter in a handful of Greek words, principally distinguishing ό,τι (*ó,ti*, 'whatever') from ότι (*óti*, 'that').
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] There are many different methods of rendering Greek text or Greek names in the Latin script.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The form in which classical Greek names are conventionally rendered in English goes back to the way Greek loanwords were incorporated into Latin in antiquity.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In this system, ⟨κ⟩ is replaced with ⟨c⟩, the diphthongs ⟨αι⟩ and ⟨οι⟩ are rendered as ⟨ae⟩ and ⟨oe⟩ (or ⟨æ,œ⟩); and ⟨ει⟩ and ⟨ου⟩ are simplified to ⟨i⟩ and ⟨u⟩.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Smooth breathing marks are usually ignored and rough breathing marks are usually rendered as the letter ⟨h⟩.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In modern scholarly transliteration of Ancient Greek, ⟨κ⟩ will usually be rendered as ⟨k⟩, and the vowel combinations ⟨αι, οι, ει, ου⟩ as ⟨ai, oi, ei, ou⟩.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The letters ⟨θ⟩ and ⟨φ⟩ are generally rendered as ⟨th⟩ and ⟨ph⟩; ⟨χ⟩ as either ⟨ch⟩ or ⟨kh⟩; and word-initial ⟨ρ⟩ as ⟨rh⟩.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Standardized formal transcription systems have been defined by the International Organization for Standardization (as ISO 843), by the United Nations Group of Experts on Geographical Names, by the Library of Congress, and others.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] During the Mycenaean period, between roughly the 16th and 12th centuries BC, a script called Linear B was used to write the earliest attested form of the Greek language, known as Mycenaean Greek.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] This writing system, unrelated to the Greek alphabet, last appeared in the 13th century BC.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Inscription written in the Greek alphabet begin to emerge from the 8th century BC onward.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] While early samples of the Greek alphabet date from at least 775 BC, the oldest known substantial and comprehensible inscriptions, such as those on the Dipylon vase, the cup of Nestor, and cup of Acesander, date from c.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] It is accepted that the introduction of the alphabet occurred some time prior to these inscriptions.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] While earlier dates have been proposed, the Greek alphabet is commonly held to have originated some time in the late 9th or early 8th century BC, conventionally around 800 BC.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The period between the use of the two writing systems, Linear B and the Greek alphabet, during which no Greek texts are attested, is known as the Greek Dark Ages.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The Greeks adopted the alphabet from the earlier Phoenician alphabet, one of the closely related scripts used for the West Semitic languages, calling it Φοινικήια γράμματα 'Phoenician letters'.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] However, the Phoenician alphabet was limited to consonants.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] When it was adopted for writing Greek, certain consonants were adapted in order to express vowels.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The use of both vowels and consonants makes Greek the first alphabet in the narrow sense, as distinguished from the abjads used in Semitic languages, which have letters only for consonants.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Greek initially took over all of the 22 letters of Phoenician.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] A doublet of *waw* was also borrowed as a consonant for [w] (Ϝ, *digamma*).
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Eventually, a seventh vowel letter for the long /ɔː/ (Ω, *omega*) was introduced.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Greek also introduced three new consonant letters for its aspirated plosive sounds and consonant clusters: Φ (*phi*) for /pʰ/, Χ (*chi*) for /kʰ/ and Ψ (*psi*) for /ps/.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In western Greek variants, Χ was instead used for /ks/ and Ψ for /kʰ/.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The origin of these letters is a matter of some debate.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Greek was originally written predominantly from right to left, just like Phoenician, but scribes could freely alternate between directions.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] For a time, a writing style with alternating right-to-left and left-to-right lines (called *boustrophedon*, literally 'ox-turning', after the manner of an ox ploughing a field) was common, until in the classical period the left-to-right writing direction became the norm.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Individual letter shapes were mirrored depending on the writing direction of the current line.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] There were initially numerous local (epichoric) variants of the Greek alphabet, which differed in the use and non-use of the additional vowel and consonant symbols and several other features.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Epichoric alphabets are commonly divided into four major types according to their different treatments of additional consonant letters for the aspirated consonants (/pʰ, kʰ/) and consonant clusters (/ks, ps/) of Greek.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] These four types are often conventionally labelled as "green", "red", "light blue" and "dark blue" types, based on a colour-coded map in a seminal 19th-century work on the topic, *Studien zur Geschichte des griechischen Alphabets* by Adolf Kirchhoff (1867).
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The "green" (or southern) type is the most archaic and closest to the Phoenician.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The "red" (or western) type is the one that was later transmitted to the West and became the ancestor of the Latin alphabet, and bears some crucial features characteristic of that later development.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The "blue" (or eastern) type is the one from which the later standard Greek alphabet emerged.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Athens used a local form of the "light blue" alphabet type until the end of the 5th century BC, which lacked the letters Ξ and Ψ as well as the vowel symbols Η and Ω.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In the Old Attic alphabet, ΧΣ stood for /ks/ and ΦΣ for /ps/. Ε was used for all three sounds /e, eː, ɛː/ (correspondinɡ to classical Ε, ΕΙ, Η), and Ο was used for all of /o, oː, ɔː/ (corresponding to classical Ο, ΟΥ, Ω).
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The letter Η (heta) was used for the consonant /h/.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Some variant local letter forms were also characteristic of Athenian writing, some of which were shared with the neighboring (but otherwise "red") alphabet of Euboia: a form of Λ that resembled a Latin *L* () and a form of Σ that resembled a Latin *S* ().
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The classical twenty-four-letter alphabet that is now used to represent the Greek language was originally the local alphabet of Ionia.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] By the late 5th century BC, it was commonly used by many Athenians.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] 403 BC, at the suggestion of the archon Eucleides, the Athenian Assembly formally abandoned the Old Attic alphabet and adopted the Ionian alphabet as part of the democratic reforms after the overthrow of the Thirty Tyrants.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Because of Eucleides's role in suggesting the idea to adopt the Ionian alphabet, the standard twenty-four-letter Greek alphabet is sometimes known as the "Eucleidean alphabet".
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Roughly thirty years later, the Eucleidean alphabet was adopted in Boeotia and it may have been adopted a few years previously in Macedonia.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] By the end of the 4th century BC, it had displaced local alphabets across the Greek-speaking world to become the standard form of the Greek alphabet.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] When the Greeks adopted the Phoenician alphabet, they took over not only the letter shapes and sound values but also the names by which the sequence of the alphabet could be recited and memorized.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In Phoenician, each letter name was a word that began with the sound represented by that letter; thus *ʾaleph*, the word for "ox", was used as the name for the glottal stop /ʔ/, *bet*, or "house", for the /b/ sound, and so on.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] When the letters were adopted by the Greeks, most of the Phoenician names were maintained or modified slightly to fit Greek phonology; thus, *ʾaleph, bet, gimel* became *alpha, beta, gamma*.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The Greek names of the following letters are more or less straightforward continuations of their Phoenician antecedents.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The name of lambda is attested in early sources as λάβδα besides λάμβδα; in Modern Greek the spelling is often λάμδα, reflecting pronunciation.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Similarly, iota is sometimes spelled γιώτα in Modern Greek ([ʝ] is conventionally transcribed ⟨γ{ι,η,υ,ει,οι}⟩ word-initially and intervocalically before back vowels and /a/).
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In the tables below, the Greek names of all letters are given in their traditional polytonic spelling; in modern practice, like with all other words, they are usually spelled in the simplified monotonic system.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In the cases of the three historical sibilant letters below, the correspondence between Phoenician and Ancient Greek is less clear, with apparent mismatches both in letter names and sound values.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The early history of these letters (and the fourth sibilant letter, obsolete san) has been a matter of some debate.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Here too, the changes in the pronunciation of the letter names between Ancient and Modern Greek are regular.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In the following group of consonant letters, the older forms of the names in Ancient Greek were spelled with -εῖ, indicating an original pronunciation with *-ē*.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In Modern Greek these names are spelled with -ι.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The following group of vowel letters were originally called simply by their sound values as long vowels: ē, ō, ū, and ɔ.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Their modern names contain adjectival qualifiers that were added during the Byzantine period, to distinguish between letters that had become confusable.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Thus, the letters ⟨ο⟩ and ⟨ω⟩, pronounced identically by this time, were called *o mikron* ("small o") and *o mega* ("big o").
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The letter ⟨ε⟩ was called *e psilon* ("plain e") to distinguish it from the identically pronounced digraph ⟨αι⟩, while, similarly, ⟨υ⟩, which at this time was pronounced [y], was called *y psilon* ("plain y") to distinguish it from the identically pronounced digraph ⟨οι⟩.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Some dialects of the Aegean and Cypriot have retained long consonants and pronounce [ˈɣamːa] and [ˈkapʰa]; also, ήτα has come to be pronounced [ˈitʰa] in Cypriot.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Like Latin and other alphabetic scripts, Greek originally had only a single form of each letter, without a distinction between uppercase and lowercase.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] This distinction is an innovation of the modern era, drawing on different lines of development of the letter shapes in earlier handwriting.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The oldest forms of the letters in antiquity are majuscule forms.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Besides the upright, straight inscriptional forms (capitals) found in stone carvings or incised pottery, more fluent writing styles adapted for handwriting on soft materials were also developed during antiquity.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Such handwriting has been preserved especially from papyrus manuscripts in Egypt since the Hellenistic period.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Ancient handwriting developed two distinct styles: uncial writing, with carefully drawn, rounded block letters of about equal size, used as a book hand for carefully produced literary and religious manuscripts, and cursive writing, used for everyday purposes.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The cursive forms approached the style of lowercase letter forms, with ascenders and descenders, as well as many connecting lines and ligatures between letters.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In the 9th and 10th centuries, uncial book hands were replaced with a new, more compact writing style, with letter forms partly adapted from the earlier cursive.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] This minuscule style remained the dominant form of handwritten Greek into the modern era.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] During the Renaissance, western printers adopted the minuscule letter forms as lowercase printed typefaces, while modeling uppercase letters on the ancient inscriptional forms.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The orthographic practice of using the letter case distinction for marking proper names, titles, etc. developed in parallel to the practice in Latin and other western languages.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Apart from the daughter alphabets listed above, which were adapted from Greek but developed into separate writing systems, the Greek alphabet has also been adopted at various times and in various places to write other languages.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] For some of them, additional letters were introduced.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Greek symbols are used as symbols in mathematics, physics and other sciences.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Many symbols have traditional uses, such as lower case epsilon (ε) for an arbitrarily small positive number, lower case pi (π) for the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter, capital sigma (Σ) for summation, and lower case sigma (σ) for standard deviation.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] For many years the Greek alphabet was used by the World Meteorological Organization for naming North Atlantic hurricanes if a season was so active that it exhausted the regular list of storm names.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] This happened during the 2005 season (when Alpha through Zeta were used), and the 2020 season (when Alpha through Iota were used), after which the practice was discontinued.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In May 2021 the World Health Organization announced that the variants of SARS-CoV-2 of the virus would be named using letters of the Greek alphabet to avoid stigma and simplify communications for non-scientific audiences.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Greek letters are used to denote the brighter stars within each of the eighty-eight constellations.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In most constellations, the brightest star is designated Alpha and the next brightest Beta etc.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] For example, the brightest star in the constellation of Centaurus is known as Alpha Centauri.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] For historical reasons, the Greek designations of some constellations begin with a lower ranked letter.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Several Greek letters are used as phonetic symbols in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA).
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Several of them denote fricative consonants; the rest stand for variants of vowel sounds.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The symbol in Americanist phonetic notation for the voiceless alveolar lateral fricative is the Greek letter lambda ⟨λ⟩, but ⟨ɬ⟩ in the IPA.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The IPA symbol for the palatal lateral approximant is ⟨ʎ⟩, which looks similar to lambda, but is actually an inverted lowercase *y*.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Greek letters were also used to write numbers.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In the classical Ionian system, the first nine letters of the alphabet stood for the numbers from 1 to 9, the next nine letters stood for the multiples of 10, from 10 to 90, and the next nine letters stood for the multiples of 100, from 100 to 900.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] For this purpose, in addition to the 24 letters which by that time made up the standard alphabet, three otherwise obsolete letters were retained or revived: digamma ⟨Ϝ⟩ for 6, koppa ⟨Ϙ⟩ for 90, and a rare Ionian letter for [ss], today called sampi ⟨Ͳ⟩, for 900.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] This system has remained in use in Greek up to the present day, although today it is only employed for limited purposes such as enumerating chapters in a book, similar to the way Roman numerals are used in English.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The three extra symbols are today written as ⟨ϛ⟩, ⟨ϟ⟩ and ⟨ϡ⟩.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] To mark a letter as a numeral sign, a small stroke called *keraia* is added to the right of it.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In North America, many college fraternities and sororities are named with combinations of Greek letters, and are hence also known as "Greek letter organizations".
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] This naming tradition was initiated by the foundation of the Phi Beta Kappa society at the College of William and Mary in 1776.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The name of this fraternal organization is an acronym for the ancient Greek phrase Φιλοσοφία Βίου Κυβερνήτης (*Philosophia Biou Kybernētēs*), which means "Love of wisdom, the guide of life" and serves as the organization's motto.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Sometimes early fraternal organizations were known by their Greek letter names because the mottos that these names stood for were secret and revealed only to members of the fraternity.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Different chapters within the same fraternity are almost always (with a handful of exceptions) designated using Greek letters as serial numbers.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The founding chapter of each organization is its A chapter.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] As an organization expands, it establishes a B chapter, a Γ chapter, and so on and so forth.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] In an organization that expands to more than 24 chapters, the chapter after Ω chapter is AA chapter, followed by AB chapter, etc.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Each of these is still a "chapter Letter", albeit a double-digit letter just as 10 through 99 are double-digit numbers.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] The Roman alphabet has a similar extended form with such double-digit letters when necessary, but it is used for columns in a table or chart rather than chapters of an organization.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] Some letters can occur in variant shapes, mostly inherited from medieval minuscule handwriting.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p01] While their use in normal typography of Greek is purely a matter of font styles, some such variants have been given separate encodings in Unicode.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] For computer usage, a variety of encodings have been used for Greek online, many of them documented in RFC 1947.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] The two principal ones still used today are ISO/IEC 8859-7 and Unicode.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] ISO 8859-7 supports only the monotonic orthography; Unicode supports both the monotonic and polytonic orthographies.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] For the range A0–FF (hex), it follows the Unicode range 370–3CF (see below) except that some symbols, like ©, ½, § etc. are used where Unicode has unused locations.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] Like all ISO-8859 encodings, it is equal to ASCII for 00–7F (hex).
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] Unicode supports polytonic orthography well enough for ordinary continuous text in modern and ancient Greek, and even many archaic forms for epigraphy.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] With the use of combining characters, Unicode also supports Greek philology and dialectology and various other specialized requirements.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] Most current text rendering engines do not render diacritics well, so, though alpha with macron and acute can be *represented* as U+03B1 U+0304 U+0301, this rarely renders well: ᾱ́.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] There are two main blocks of Greek characters in Unicode.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] The first is "Greek and Coptic" (U+0370 to U+03FF).
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] This block is based on ISO 8859-7 and is sufficient to write Modern Greek.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] There are also some archaic letters and Greek-based technical symbols.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] This block also supports the Coptic alphabet.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] Formerly, most Coptic letters shared codepoints with similar-looking Greek letters; but in many scholarly works, both scripts occur, with quite different letter shapes, so as of Unicode 4.1, Coptic and Greek were disunified.
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] Those Coptic letters with no Greek equivalents still remain in this block (U+03E2 to U+03EF).
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] To write polytonic Greek, one may use combining diacritical marks or the precomposed characters in the "Greek Extended" block (U+1F00 to U+1FFF).
[src:greek-alphabet/greek-alphabet-p02] IBM code pages 437, 860, 861, 862, 863, and 865 contain the letters ΓΘΣΦΩαδεπστφ (plus β as an alternative interpretation for ß).
